00:04:58.630 --> 00:05:00.932
So here are the nice
pictures of bats.

00:05:00.932 --> 00:05:02.015
They're beautiful animals.

00:05:05.310 --> 00:05:07.850
They have specializations,
of course, for hearing.

00:05:07.850 --> 00:05:12.110
They have large pinnae, right?

00:05:12.110 --> 00:05:15.010
Much, much larger
than other animals,

00:05:15.010 --> 00:05:16.405
especially for their size.

00:05:18.440 --> 00:05:21.670
They have very small eyes.

00:05:21.670 --> 00:05:24.365
And their visual systems
are not well developed.

00:05:26.420 --> 00:05:27.710
They of course have wings.

00:05:27.710 --> 00:05:29.095
So these are flying animals.

00:05:30.620 --> 00:05:33.310
And many of them
have noseleaves.

00:05:34.780 --> 00:05:38.350
So here's a nose
cartilage that's

00:05:38.350 --> 00:05:43.540
very well developed because
these animals emit sound.

00:05:43.540 --> 00:05:45.710
Their echolocation
pulse is emitted.

00:05:45.710 --> 00:05:47.714
And some of the sound
comes out of the mouth.

00:05:47.714 --> 00:05:49.255
But some of it comes
out of the nose.

00:05:50.400 --> 00:05:55.400
And this noseleaf tends
to focus the sound forward

00:05:55.400 --> 00:05:58.760
because that's where the bat
is interested at detecting

00:05:58.760 --> 00:06:03.290
some kind of a target,
like the insect prey

00:06:03.290 --> 00:06:04.880
that most of these bats eat.

00:06:04.880 --> 00:06:09.520
So I should backtrack
and say that we're really

00:06:09.520 --> 00:06:14.605
talking about three
types of bats.

00:06:16.460 --> 00:06:19.790
We're talking about echolocating
bats, of which there

00:06:19.790 --> 00:06:24.110
are two varieties that I'll
tell you about it in a minute.

00:06:24.110 --> 00:06:30.035
And we're also not going to talk
about non-echolocating bats.

00:06:37.070 --> 00:06:40.060
And sometimes, these
non-echolocating bats

00:06:40.060 --> 00:06:43.985
are called fruit-eating bats.

00:06:46.710 --> 00:06:48.395
They are also flying mammals.

00:06:49.990 --> 00:06:51.990
But they have big eyes.

00:06:51.990 --> 00:06:54.740
They have relatively
small pinnae.

00:06:54.740 --> 00:06:58.210
And they navigate around
like birds and other mammals,

00:06:58.210 --> 00:06:59.870
using their visual system.

00:06:59.870 --> 00:07:01.050
So they don't echolocate.

00:07:03.630 --> 00:07:05.380
So you have
non-echolocating bats

00:07:05.380 --> 00:07:07.280
that we're not
going to talk about.

00:07:07.280 --> 00:07:10.350
We have echolocating bats
that we will talk about.

00:07:11.920 --> 00:07:14.380
It's starting to get confusing
with all these groups.

00:07:14.380 --> 00:07:18.630
In fact, bats are a very
successful group of mammals.

00:07:18.630 --> 00:07:20.780
Supposedly, there
are more species

00:07:20.780 --> 00:07:24.180
of bats than all other
mammals combined.

00:07:24.180 --> 00:07:27.530
It's and amazingly
successful group of mammals.

00:07:27.530 --> 00:07:32.010
And mostly because
echolocation has opened up

00:07:32.010 --> 00:07:34.490
a whole new vista for bats.

00:07:34.490 --> 00:07:38.720
Not only can they fly around,
but they can do so at night--

00:07:38.720 --> 00:07:41.650
in total darkness--
and find prey,

00:07:41.650 --> 00:07:43.910
their targets, their insects.

00:07:43.910 --> 00:07:46.700
So instead of
being fruit eating,

00:07:46.700 --> 00:07:48.753
these echolocating
bats are carnivorous.

00:07:52.260 --> 00:07:55.410
Most of them eat insects
that they catch on the wing.

00:07:55.410 --> 00:07:57.510
So flying insects.

00:07:57.510 --> 00:08:00.430
But there are
gleaning bats that eat

00:08:00.430 --> 00:08:01.955
insects on the forest floor.

00:08:03.200 --> 00:08:08.220
There are vampire bats
that cut little holes

00:08:08.220 --> 00:08:12.470
in the top of mammals and lap
up the blood that comes out.

00:08:12.470 --> 00:08:15.790
There are fish eating
bats that eat fish.

00:08:15.790 --> 00:08:18.615
There are a whole
variety types of bats.

00:08:18.615 --> 00:08:21.270
But most of them eat insects
that they catch on the wing.

00:08:22.410 --> 00:08:24.560
And we'll have a
demonstration of that.

00:08:24.560 --> 00:08:26.490
So these are insect
eating bats here.

00:08:29.240 --> 00:08:32.830
This one I want to
point out its name for.

00:08:32.830 --> 00:08:36.830
This one is called-- in the
middle left, right here--

00:08:36.830 --> 00:08:38.620
megaderma lyra.

00:08:38.620 --> 00:08:40.220
So mega means big.

00:08:41.260 --> 00:08:43.120
Derma means skin, ?

00:08:43.120 --> 00:08:43.620
right?

00:08:43.620 --> 00:08:45.805
It's so named because
of it's big skin here.

00:08:47.160 --> 00:08:50.400
And lyra refers to
lyrical, or musical,

00:08:50.400 --> 00:08:52.250
or something that sings, OK?

00:08:52.250 --> 00:08:53.450
So these bats are singing.

00:08:55.340 --> 00:08:58.380
Let's look at the types
of singing that they do.

00:09:00.290 --> 00:09:07.240
And this display
shows the two types

00:09:07.240 --> 00:09:09.250
of signals that are
emitted by the two

00:09:09.250 --> 00:09:12.120
big groups of echolocating bats.

00:09:12.120 --> 00:09:14.950
The first I want to start
with is the simplest.

00:09:14.950 --> 00:09:16.555
It's called an FM bat.

00:09:17.790 --> 00:09:22.740
An FM-- you have
an FM radio that

00:09:22.740 --> 00:09:35.010
stands for frequency
modulated, or Fm.

00:09:37.310 --> 00:09:37.860
OK?

00:09:37.860 --> 00:09:47.420
And in this graph of the FM
bat's echolocating signal--

00:09:47.420 --> 00:09:50.670
this graph is called
a spectrogram--

00:09:50.670 --> 00:09:52.911
and it plots the
frequency on the y-axis

00:09:52.911 --> 00:09:57.760
and as a function of
time on the x-axis.

00:09:57.760 --> 00:10:01.970
And this echolocating
pulse is the thing

00:10:01.970 --> 00:10:03.229
that the bat is emitting.

00:10:03.229 --> 00:10:04.395
It's producing and emitting.

00:10:05.440 --> 00:10:08.070
And the reason it's
frequency modulated is it

00:10:08.070 --> 00:10:11.420
starts at a high frequency
and modulates down

00:10:11.420 --> 00:10:12.315
to a lower frequency.

00:10:13.490 --> 00:10:15.070
And here's another one.

00:10:15.070 --> 00:10:16.730
And here's another one.

00:10:16.730 --> 00:10:19.340
Now, if there's a
target out there,

00:10:19.340 --> 00:10:24.640
some distance from the bat,
this pulse that goes out

00:10:24.640 --> 00:10:26.210
will be reflected
off the target.

00:10:26.210 --> 00:10:30.250
And then it will come back to
the bat in the form of an echo

00:10:30.250 --> 00:10:31.310
sometime later.

00:10:32.740 --> 00:10:33.240
OK?

00:10:33.240 --> 00:10:36.800
So the bat-- in this
case the FM bat--

00:10:36.800 --> 00:10:39.710
gets information, number
one, if there's an echo,

00:10:39.710 --> 00:10:41.600
there's a target out there.

00:10:41.600 --> 00:10:46.470
And number two, the time
between the pulse and the echo

00:10:46.470 --> 00:10:49.440
is an indication of the distance
the target is from the bat,

00:10:49.440 --> 00:10:49.940
right?

00:10:49.940 --> 00:10:54.070
Because the sound has to go
from the bat, to the target,

00:10:54.070 --> 00:10:56.055
and then from the
target back to the bat.

00:10:57.290 --> 00:11:01.250
And we know that the
sound velocity in air

00:11:01.250 --> 00:11:05.060
is about 340 meters per second.

00:11:09.590 --> 00:11:12.000
So knowing that
velocity, and knowing

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:16.410
the time between the pulse and
the echo, we-- and the bat--

00:11:16.410 --> 00:11:18.600
can get information
of how far away

00:11:18.600 --> 00:11:20.305
the target is from the bat.

00:11:22.270 --> 00:11:25.550
Now, a couple of things
I want to comment here

00:11:25.550 --> 00:11:26.460
on this spectrogram.

00:11:26.460 --> 00:11:28.920
Number one, the frequency axis.

00:11:28.920 --> 00:11:32.130
You might not be able to see
it, but it starts at zero

00:11:32.130 --> 00:11:34.550
and then quickly
jumps to 30 kilohertz.

00:11:36.090 --> 00:11:38.760
And then there's
60, 90, and 120.

00:11:38.760 --> 00:11:42.040
So those are very
high sound frequency.

00:11:42.040 --> 00:11:47.380
And so, in the early days
and to a certain extent

00:11:47.380 --> 00:11:50.327
still, those frequencies
would be called ultrasonic.

00:11:57.420 --> 00:11:59.820
And there's no real
good reason for that,

00:11:59.820 --> 00:12:01.840
except that we're humans.

00:12:01.840 --> 00:12:05.810
And everything is important
with respect to humans.

00:12:05.810 --> 00:12:09.500
And our upper limit of
frequency, as you well

00:12:09.500 --> 00:12:12.430
know-- if you're a
very young human--

00:12:12.430 --> 00:12:14.640
ends at about 20 kilohertz.

00:12:14.640 --> 00:12:18.309
And most of us, who are in
our middle or older ages,

00:12:18.309 --> 00:12:20.100
aren't hearing anything
above 10 kilohertz.

00:12:21.240 --> 00:12:24.630
So all these frequencies
emitted by the bat,

00:12:24.630 --> 00:12:27.372
and the echoes coming
back, are beyond the range

00:12:27.372 --> 00:12:28.080
of human hearing.

00:12:29.640 --> 00:12:31.810
And in that sense,
they're ultrasonic.

00:12:31.810 --> 00:12:34.465
So you can't go out and say, oh.

00:12:34.465 --> 00:12:37.080
I heard a bat, or
at least in terms

00:12:37.080 --> 00:12:41.200
of the echolocating signals
that the bats are emitting.

00:12:41.200 --> 00:12:43.600
There are some
sounds that bats emit

00:12:43.600 --> 00:12:46.160
that are communication sounds.

00:12:46.160 --> 00:12:47.970
And those are in
the human frequency

00:12:47.970 --> 00:12:49.410
range to a certain extent.

00:12:49.410 --> 00:12:51.570
But almost all the
echolocating signals

00:12:51.570 --> 00:12:55.610
are well above the upper
limit of our hearing range.

00:12:56.690 --> 00:12:59.640
Now, another thing that you
can see from this spectrogram

00:12:59.640 --> 00:13:03.120
is that there's a big
delay between this pulse

00:13:03.120 --> 00:13:05.150
and this echo, OK?

00:13:05.150 --> 00:13:06.780
The target is pretty far away.

00:13:07.830 --> 00:13:10.810
Generally, bats
head toward targets.

00:13:10.810 --> 00:13:12.310
And this has been
shown many times

00:13:12.310 --> 00:13:15.290
in behavioral experiments,
especially if they're hungry.

00:13:16.110 --> 00:13:16.610
OK?

00:13:16.610 --> 00:13:19.260
And as the bat gets closer
and closer to the target,

00:13:19.260 --> 00:13:23.824
obviously the time between the
pulse and the returning echo

00:13:23.824 --> 00:13:24.365
gets shorter.

00:13:26.390 --> 00:13:30.720
And, as you can probably
see from this spectrogram,

00:13:30.720 --> 00:13:34.910
there are a lot more
pulses emitted per time

00:13:34.910 --> 00:13:38.070
when the bat gets
close to the target

00:13:38.070 --> 00:13:40.869
because the bat is interested
in getting a lot of information

00:13:40.869 --> 00:13:41.660
when it gets close.

00:13:42.850 --> 00:13:46.300
Another reason that the bat
doesn't emit very many pulses

00:13:46.300 --> 00:13:47.840
when it's far away
from the target

00:13:47.840 --> 00:13:51.750
is, if you emitted a pulse
before the echo returned,

00:13:51.750 --> 00:13:55.125
you could get confused
between the outgoing pulse

00:13:55.125 --> 00:13:56.340
and the returning echo.

00:13:57.410 --> 00:14:00.870
So typically, bats tend to
increase their pulse rate

00:14:00.870 --> 00:14:03.740
a lot more as they get
closer to their target.

00:14:03.740 --> 00:14:04.240
OK?

00:14:04.240 --> 00:14:07.290
And I'm going to show you
a demonstration of that.

00:14:07.290 --> 00:14:09.790
I'm sure we'll
convince you of that.

00:14:09.790 --> 00:14:14.730
So this is the type of bat
we have here in New England.

00:14:14.730 --> 00:14:18.350
Examples of this are a little
brown bat or the big brown bat.

00:14:19.630 --> 00:14:23.400
And if anybody has seen
bats-- have you guys seen bats

00:14:23.400 --> 00:14:25.011
flying around at night?

00:14:25.011 --> 00:14:25.510
Yeah?

00:14:25.510 --> 00:14:26.700
