00:14:40.960 --> 00:14:43.720
I sometimes see them
if I'm out canoeing

00:14:43.720 --> 00:14:47.020
on a lake at night,
or in the evening.

00:14:47.020 --> 00:14:48.060
Any other places?

00:14:48.060 --> 00:14:49.685
On golf courses, for example.

00:14:51.170 --> 00:14:54.720
And those are all
sensible, if you will,

00:14:54.720 --> 00:14:57.600
places for the bat to hunt
because they're very open

00:14:57.600 --> 00:14:58.100
situations.

00:14:59.230 --> 00:15:02.460
And there isn't a whole bunch
of clutter, if you will,

00:15:02.460 --> 00:15:05.170
that will return
echoes to the bat.

00:15:05.170 --> 00:15:07.610
If there's a moth or a
mosquito out there-- it

00:15:07.610 --> 00:15:10.520
might be the only
thing out there

00:15:10.520 --> 00:15:12.890
above the surface of
the lake, and that's

00:15:12.890 --> 00:15:15.690
very interesting to the bat
because it has one target.

00:15:15.690 --> 00:15:18.920
It doesn't have a million leaves
of the forest, if you will,

00:15:18.920 --> 00:15:20.390
to get confused.

00:15:20.390 --> 00:15:22.780
It gets one echo, it knows
there's one target out there.

00:15:22.780 --> 00:15:24.710
It goes and swoops out there.

00:15:24.710 --> 00:15:28.430
And it possibly eats the
target, if it's an insect.

00:15:30.111 --> 00:15:30.610
OK.

00:15:35.900 --> 00:15:38.020
Let me give you
some other examples

00:15:38.020 --> 00:15:40.060
of some information on FM bats.

00:15:40.060 --> 00:15:42.640
First, I want to
point your attention

00:15:42.640 --> 00:15:46.490
to who discovered
echolocating bats.

00:15:46.490 --> 00:15:47.830
And I have his book here.

00:15:48.940 --> 00:15:51.730
This is Donald Griffin's book.

00:15:51.730 --> 00:15:53.255
It's called Listening
In the Dark.

00:15:54.800 --> 00:15:59.015
And I'll write his
name on the board.

00:16:07.500 --> 00:16:10.972
And I'd like to do just a
short reading from his book.

00:16:10.972 --> 00:16:12.510
Then I'll pass it around.

00:16:14.640 --> 00:16:16.420
So this is the
section where he talks

00:16:16.420 --> 00:16:21.520
about this discovery of
bats' ultrasonic sounds.

00:16:27.240 --> 00:16:31.280
So he writes, "during my
undergraduate years at Harvard

00:16:31.280 --> 00:16:35.520
College, when I was actively
engaged in banding bats

00:16:35.520 --> 00:16:38.800
to study their
migration--" So bats here,

00:16:38.800 --> 00:16:42.290
about this time of year, start
flying south like birds do.

00:16:44.130 --> 00:16:46.970
He says, "I was familiar only
with the generally held view

00:16:46.970 --> 00:16:51.860
that bats felt with their wings
the proximity of obstacles."

00:16:51.860 --> 00:16:55.110
that was how people thought
they navigated around, by touch.

00:17:00.580 --> 00:17:02.580
"Several friends suggested
that I experiment

00:17:02.580 --> 00:17:05.720
with the ability of my
bats to avoid obstacles."

00:17:05.720 --> 00:17:07.460
Blah, blah, blah.

00:17:07.460 --> 00:17:12.140
"I decided that I should contact
a professor in the Harvard

00:17:12.140 --> 00:17:13.790
physics department.

00:17:13.790 --> 00:17:17.560
That was Professor GW Pierce,
inventor of the Pierce circuit

00:17:17.560 --> 00:17:19.930
for the stabilization of
radio frequency oscillator.

00:17:22.130 --> 00:17:25.270
Pierce had developed almost
the only apparatus then

00:17:25.270 --> 00:17:28.069
in existence that could
detect and generate

00:17:28.069 --> 00:17:32.660
a wide range of sounds
lying above the audio range.

00:17:32.660 --> 00:17:38.570
That is from 20,000 to almost
100,000 cycles per second.

00:17:38.570 --> 00:17:42.800
With some trepidation, I
approached Professor Pierce

00:17:42.800 --> 00:17:46.520
in the winter of 1938
with the suggestion

00:17:46.520 --> 00:17:48.960
that we use his apparatus
to listen to my bats.

00:17:50.470 --> 00:17:52.960
I found him eager to
try the experiment,

00:17:52.960 --> 00:17:54.430
particularly since
he was already

00:17:54.430 --> 00:17:56.790
engaged in extensive studies
of the high frequency

00:17:56.790 --> 00:17:57.880
sounds of insects.

00:17:59.970 --> 00:18:03.690
When I first brought
a cage full of bats,

00:18:03.690 --> 00:18:07.550
myotis lucifugus--" OK,
that's the little brown bat--

00:18:07.550 --> 00:18:10.130
"to Pierce's lab
and held the cage

00:18:10.130 --> 00:18:12.340
in front of the
parabolic horn, we

00:18:12.340 --> 00:18:16.520
were surprised and delighted to
hear a medley of raucous noises

00:18:16.520 --> 00:18:18.270
from the loudspeaker."

00:18:18.270 --> 00:18:22.850
So Griffin, as an
undergraduate, discovered

00:18:22.850 --> 00:18:27.520
that bats emitted
ultrasonic stimuli, OK?

00:18:27.520 --> 00:18:32.745
And he went on to pursue a
lifetime of research on bats.

00:18:33.920 --> 00:18:35.910
While he was still
an undergraduate,

00:18:35.910 --> 00:18:38.900
he designed some
experiments to see

00:18:38.900 --> 00:18:43.110
if the bats could use this
echolocation to avoid objects.

00:18:43.110 --> 00:18:46.940
And so he took a room,
turned out all the lights

00:18:46.940 --> 00:18:49.740
so the bats could
only use other senses.

00:18:49.740 --> 00:18:51.930
And he noticed that
they would fly around.

00:18:51.930 --> 00:18:56.210
And he didn't have a very
extensive equipment budget,

00:18:56.210 --> 00:19:01.480
so for objects, he went to the
store that sold piano wire.

00:19:01.480 --> 00:19:03.700
And he strung piano
wire from the ceiling

00:19:03.700 --> 00:19:05.770
to the floor of the room.

00:19:05.770 --> 00:19:07.690
And he let the bats fly around.

00:19:07.690 --> 00:19:10.730
And he knew that if something
touched the piano wire,

00:19:10.730 --> 00:19:15.280
he could hear a little
sound of the wire vibrating.

00:19:15.280 --> 00:19:18.480
And he had to go
down in diameter,

00:19:18.480 --> 00:19:21.760
to piano wire that was
the thickness of the width

00:19:21.760 --> 00:19:25.000
of a human hair,
before the bats finally

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:26.950
started touching the wire.

00:19:26.950 --> 00:19:30.900
They could detect objects
even sub-millimeter in size.

00:19:30.900 --> 00:19:34.740
So their sense of echolocation
was really well developed,

00:19:34.740 --> 00:19:36.090
and very good.

00:19:36.090 --> 00:19:37.855
It could detect
very tiny targets.

00:19:39.370 --> 00:19:42.665
So that was one of his first,
and foremost, experiments.

00:19:44.437 --> 00:19:45.770
Now, I have some demonstrations.

00:19:47.240 --> 00:19:52.530
And some of them are from
Griffin's original work.

00:19:52.530 --> 00:20:00.540
And so, in these
demonstrations, you

00:20:00.540 --> 00:20:02.890
have a movie of the bat flying.

00:20:03.990 --> 00:20:08.940
And the target, this
time, is a small food item

00:20:08.940 --> 00:20:09.775
that's thrown up.

00:20:09.775 --> 00:20:10.775
I think it's a mealworm.

00:20:11.810 --> 00:20:14.580
So the investigator
throws up the mealworm.

00:20:14.580 --> 00:20:16.450
And the bat catches it.

00:20:16.450 --> 00:20:20.700
And on the audio
part of the track,

00:20:20.700 --> 00:20:23.160
you'll hear some popping.

00:20:23.160 --> 00:20:27.970
And I think that's a stroboscope
that's illuminating the image.

00:20:27.970 --> 00:20:30.530
You will also hear
a little chirp.

00:20:30.530 --> 00:20:32.590
And they're pretty
high frequency.

00:20:32.590 --> 00:20:36.010
But that is the bat
echolocating pulse going out.

00:20:36.010 --> 00:20:39.560
It's detected by
microphone, and transformed

00:20:39.560 --> 00:20:42.470
from the high frequencies
down into lower frequencies

00:20:42.470 --> 00:20:45.680
in your audio range,
so you can hear it.

00:20:45.680 --> 00:20:46.730
OK?

00:20:46.730 --> 00:20:49.950
And notice that,
number one, when

00:20:49.950 --> 00:20:53.010
the bat gets close to the
target, the chirps increase

00:20:53.010 --> 00:20:54.340
in frequency.

00:20:54.340 --> 00:20:56.350
And number two,
when the bat eats

00:20:56.350 --> 00:20:58.630
the target, the
chirps stop, right?

00:20:58.630 --> 00:21:02.690
Because unlike you or me,
they can't talk and eat

00:21:02.690 --> 00:21:03.690
at the same time.

00:21:09.010 --> 00:21:13.845
So those chirps are the
bat echolocating pulse.

00:21:15.485 --> 00:21:16.110
Here's the bat.

00:21:18.540 --> 00:21:20.235
Here's the target coming up.

00:21:25.620 --> 00:21:28.530
In that case, as
sometimes happens,

00:21:28.530 --> 00:21:30.950
the bat missed the target.

00:21:30.950 --> 00:21:32.040
So it's falling away.

00:21:43.600 --> 00:21:45.160
Here's the target coming up.

00:21:46.760 --> 00:21:50.090
In this case, the bat caught
it in the tip of its wing.

00:21:50.090 --> 00:21:52.120
And it brings the wing
in toward its mouth.

00:21:52.120 --> 00:21:54.090
And it eats the target.

00:21:54.090 --> 00:21:56.870
And it starts pulsing
again after it's

00:21:56.870 --> 00:21:57.960
swallowed the target.

00:22:08.115 --> 00:22:10.240
And there, I think it caught
it right in its mouth,

00:22:10.240 --> 00:22:11.750
without having to use its wings.

00:22:20.850 --> 00:22:21.350
OK.

00:22:21.350 --> 00:22:27.000
So these are some other films
that I won't go through.

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:28.890
But they were some
experiments that Griffin

00:22:28.890 --> 00:22:34.610
did, testing the ability of
bats-- and certain species--

00:22:34.610 --> 00:22:36.730
to actually catch fish.

00:22:36.730 --> 00:22:40.690
And he was mystified about
this because-- as we've

00:22:40.690 --> 00:22:42.400
talked about--
sound and air, when

00:22:42.400 --> 00:22:46.510
it comes to a fluid boundary,
mostly reflects off.

00:22:46.510 --> 00:22:50.290
So it seemed unimaginable
that the bat echolocating

00:22:50.290 --> 00:22:52.770
pulse could go under
the water and would

00:22:52.770 --> 00:22:54.190
be reflected of the fish.

00:22:54.190 --> 00:22:57.650
So what he figured out
later is that, when

00:22:57.650 --> 00:23:00.510
there is a smooth
surface of the water,

00:23:00.510 --> 00:23:04.090
the bats did not
seem interested.

00:23:04.090 --> 00:23:06.060
But when the fish
came up and rippled

00:23:06.060 --> 00:23:09.370
the surface of the water,
that was what the bats we're

00:23:09.370 --> 00:23:12.000
actually detecting,
the little ripples

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:14.515
on the surface of the water--
just as you see them visually.

00:23:18.120 --> 00:23:22.030
There's some videos of
bats catching fish here.

00:23:22.030 --> 00:23:23.250
Bats hanging out.

00:23:34.930 --> 00:23:36.960
Bats flying in rooms.

00:23:36.960 --> 00:23:37.960
Sorry about that.

00:23:41.330 --> 00:23:49.020
Now this last part of the demo
is from more modern experiments

00:23:49.020 --> 00:23:53.170
in which the bat
approaches a target.

00:23:53.170 --> 00:23:56.040
In this case, the target
is somewhere here.

00:23:56.040 --> 00:23:57.250
And it's tethered.

00:23:57.250 --> 00:23:58.285
The target is fixed.

00:23:59.620 --> 00:24:02.910
This is a spectrogram of
the bat echolocating pulse.

00:24:04.020 --> 00:24:08.420
And this is the bat
flying, in slow motion,

00:24:08.420 --> 00:24:09.345
to catch the target.

00:24:11.670 --> 00:24:13.460
And you can see the
tremendous increase

00:24:13.460 --> 00:24:15.450
in pulse repetition rate.

00:24:15.450 --> 00:24:17.850
As it eats the target,
it stops vocalizing.

00:24:19.190 --> 00:24:22.320
And now it starts again.

00:24:22.320 --> 00:24:25.610
And this'll be
repeated at least once.

00:24:25.610 --> 00:24:27.050
So here's another run.

00:24:27.050 --> 00:24:29.795
Here's the bat
spectrogram down here.

00:24:32.220 --> 00:24:33.830
And here's the bat coming in.

00:24:33.830 --> 00:24:35.350
Here is the target, right there.

00:24:57.820 --> 00:24:59.080
I guess I'd better stop that.

00:25:01.901 --> 00:25:02.400
OK.

00:25:02.400 --> 00:25:16.260
And so that second demo is
from Doctor Cynthia Moss,

00:25:16.260 --> 00:25:17.430
who used to be at Harvard.

00:25:17.430 --> 00:25:20.070
And now she's at the
University of Maryland.

00:25:20.070 --> 00:25:22.810
And she does extensive
work on bat echolocation.

00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:30.460
And so I think it clearly
shows the increase

00:25:30.460 --> 00:25:33.510
in pulse repetition rate as the
bat gets close to the target.

00:25:35.250 --> 00:25:36.310
Any questions on that?

00:25:38.050 --> 00:25:38.550
OK.

00:25:38.550 --> 00:25:43.770
So those were all the first
kind of bat I talked about,

00:25:43.770 --> 00:25:44.860
the FM bat.

00:25:48.170 --> 00:25:51.700
And now, let's get into
the second group of bats.

00:25:51.700 --> 00:25:57.491
And this group is
called CFFM bats.

00:25:57.491 --> 00:25:57.990
OK.

00:26:00.020 --> 00:26:03.390
And these are completely
different species of bats.

00:26:03.390 --> 00:26:08.440
They are new world CFFM bats
and old world CFFM bats.

00:26:08.440 --> 00:26:10.475
It probably has
evolved several times.

00:26:12.180 --> 00:26:17.160
The echolocating pulse and
echo are completely different,

00:26:17.160 --> 00:26:19.160
compared to the FM bat.

00:26:19.160 --> 00:26:22.100
So in the case of the
mustache bat, which

00:26:22.100 --> 00:26:26.110
is an example of CFFM bat,
this is the spectrogram.

00:26:26.110 --> 00:26:30.420
Again, frequency on the
y-axis and time on the x-axis.

00:26:32.340 --> 00:26:37.250
But in this case, instead of
the pulse sweeping downward,

00:26:37.250 --> 00:26:39.900
or a frequency modulated
very downward-- almost

00:26:39.900 --> 00:26:45.870
like a chirp-- instead, the
pulse is a constant frequency.

00:26:45.870 --> 00:26:49.340
So the CF stands for
constant frequency.

00:26:49.340 --> 00:26:51.360
That just means the
frequency is staying

00:26:51.360 --> 00:26:53.900
constant as a function of time.

00:26:53.900 --> 00:26:55.830
And that's this
flat section here.

00:26:58.230 --> 00:27:02.070
In the case of bat sounds,
just like human speech sounds,

00:27:02.070 --> 00:27:03.195
there are many harmonics.

00:27:04.730 --> 00:27:07.860
There's the first harmonic.

00:27:07.860 --> 00:27:09.050
That's called CF1.

00:27:10.930 --> 00:27:15.740
There's the second harmonic,
an octave above, CF2.

00:27:17.450 --> 00:27:19.340
There's a third harmonic, CF3.

00:27:20.750 --> 00:27:23.000
And there's a fourth
harmonic, CF4.

00:27:25.490 --> 00:27:30.190
And it's conventional on this
kind of spectrogram display

00:27:30.190 --> 00:27:33.150
to illustrate the sounds
that have the most

00:27:33.150 --> 00:27:36.840
energy with the
boldest marking here.

00:27:36.840 --> 00:27:42.560
So CF2 is the one that has the
highest sound pressure level.

00:27:42.560 --> 00:27:44.960
And so that's the darkest here.

00:27:44.960 --> 00:27:50.470
These other ones, especially
CF1 and CF4, are lower in level.

00:27:50.470 --> 00:27:51.970
They're not as intense.

00:27:51.970 --> 00:27:54.750
And so they're not as
black on this display.

00:27:54.750 --> 00:27:59.240
And in this display of the FM
bat, the pulse is very intense.

00:27:59.240 --> 00:28:02.510
And the echo is, of
course, much reduced.

00:28:03.520 --> 00:28:06.340
Echolocating pulses
can be 110 dB,

00:28:06.340 --> 00:28:09.920
if you measure them
right at the bat's mouth.

00:28:09.920 --> 00:28:11.810
They can be very intense.

00:28:11.810 --> 00:28:14.660
And, of course, the bat
contracts its middle ear

00:28:14.660 --> 00:28:18.410
muscles to prevent those
kinds of intense stimuli

00:28:18.410 --> 00:28:20.870
from damaging its own ears.

00:28:20.870 --> 00:28:24.410
And then it relaxes the
muscles when the echo comes by,

00:28:24.410 --> 00:28:26.985
and its hearing is fine.

00:28:28.070 --> 00:28:28.570
OK.

00:28:28.570 --> 00:28:34.890
So at the end of the CF portion,
this echo-locating pulse.

00:28:34.890 --> 00:28:37.390
There is a little FM sweep.

00:28:37.390 --> 00:28:37.890
OK.

00:28:37.890 --> 00:28:39.780
So you can appreciate,
maybe, that there's

00:28:39.780 --> 00:28:45.670
an FM1, a little FM2
sweep, a little FM3

00:28:45.670 --> 00:28:48.370
sweep, and a little Fm4 sweep.

00:28:50.050 --> 00:28:57.030
And it's thought that this
bat uses the FM of the pulse,

00:28:57.030 --> 00:28:59.860
and the FM of the
return echo, to get

00:28:59.860 --> 00:29:03.290
a measure of the distance that
the target is from the bat.

00:29:04.261 --> 00:29:04.760
OK.

00:29:04.760 --> 00:29:07.664
It if comes back
in 10 milliseconds,

00:29:07.664 --> 00:29:09.080
and you know the
sound of velocity

00:29:09.080 --> 00:29:12.450
is 340 meters per second,
you can figure out

00:29:12.450 --> 00:29:13.660
how close that is.

00:29:15.020 --> 00:29:16.940
And this bat can
do that, as well.

00:29:16.940 --> 00:29:19.340
Now, what's going on
with this CF part?

00:29:21.200 --> 00:29:25.940
Well, as you can see
on the spectrogram,

00:29:25.940 --> 00:29:29.670
the CF of the pulse
is not exactly

00:29:29.670 --> 00:29:32.420
the same as the CF of the echo.

00:29:33.850 --> 00:29:34.570
OK.

00:29:34.570 --> 00:29:38.100
The echo has shifted up to be
a little higher in frequency

00:29:38.100 --> 00:29:38.790
in each case.

00:29:40.020 --> 00:29:41.520
Now, how can
frequencies be shifted?

00:29:42.780 --> 00:29:45.260
Well, it has to do
with the Doppler shift.

00:30:12.380 --> 00:30:12.880
OK.

00:30:12.880 --> 00:30:17.410
So this is a shift in, in
this case, sound frequency.

00:30:24.120 --> 00:30:26.955
But you can have a Doppler
shift for any kind of wave.

00:30:28.040 --> 00:30:31.300
For example, you can have a
Doppler shift for light waves.

00:30:32.840 --> 00:30:35.010
If you've studied
the Big Bang theory

00:30:35.010 --> 00:30:38.370
of the origin of the universe,
there's a big explosion, right?

00:30:38.370 --> 00:30:42.620
Everything exploded out and
is moving far away from us.

00:30:42.620 --> 00:30:45.230
So you look at the light
coming from a star that's

00:30:45.230 --> 00:30:47.400
moving away from you.

00:30:47.400 --> 00:30:52.400
It's actually shifted a little
bit to longer wavelengths,

00:30:52.400 --> 00:30:55.070
toward the more reddish
hues, because it's

00:30:55.070 --> 00:30:56.200
moving away from you.

00:30:57.880 --> 00:31:02.260
So Doppler shifts have to
do with wave sources that

00:31:02.260 --> 00:31:04.440
are moving relative
to the receiver,

00:31:04.440 --> 00:31:07.550
or the receiver moving
relative to the emitter.

00:31:09.120 --> 00:31:12.590
Another example of a Doppler
shift, this time for sound,

00:31:12.590 --> 00:31:16.770
would be if you were in the
grandstand of a race track,

00:31:16.770 --> 00:31:18.970
and the race cars were
going around a big oval.

00:31:20.150 --> 00:31:20.650
OK.

00:31:20.650 --> 00:31:22.316
And you hear the sound
of their engines.

00:31:23.330 --> 00:31:27.930
As the race car comes toward
you, along the straight away,

00:31:27.930 --> 00:31:29.620
it sounds like it's
higher in pitch

00:31:29.620 --> 00:31:31.340
because it's moving toward you.

00:31:32.930 --> 00:31:37.910
As it passes you and then
starts to move away from you,

00:31:37.910 --> 00:31:39.710
it sounds like it's
lower in pitch.

00:31:39.710 --> 00:31:46.320
So the thing you'd
hear would be [BUZZING]

00:31:46.320 --> 00:31:49.660
as each race car went by you.

00:31:49.660 --> 00:31:54.630
So, as the race car is here, and
you're the observer listening

00:31:54.630 --> 00:31:58.320
here, it emits-- let's
say-- a pulse of sound.

00:32:00.461 --> 00:32:00.960
OK.

00:32:00.960 --> 00:32:03.210
This might be the peak
of the wave front,

00:32:03.210 --> 00:32:08.010
if it were just a
sinusoid, let's say.

00:32:09.450 --> 00:32:12.700
Now, by the time a race
car coming toward you

00:32:12.700 --> 00:32:16.940
has emitted the next peak,
the race car's actually moved.

00:32:18.120 --> 00:32:19.020
OK.

00:32:19.020 --> 00:32:20.350
So the peak is here.

00:32:20.350 --> 00:32:22.620
And the next peak is emitted.

00:32:22.620 --> 00:32:23.950
And it's very close together.

00:32:25.060 --> 00:32:27.740
If the race car is
moving away from you,

00:32:27.740 --> 00:32:29.960
it emits one peak of sound.

00:32:29.960 --> 00:32:32.850
And then by the time it
emits the next peak of sound,

00:32:32.850 --> 00:32:35.130
it's moved a little
away from you.

00:32:35.130 --> 00:32:37.275
The peaks are farther apart.

00:32:38.620 --> 00:32:42.490
And we know the sound source
that has a quick oscillation

00:32:42.490 --> 00:32:43.865
sounds like a high frequency.

00:32:45.520 --> 00:32:48.700
And the sound source that
has a very slow oscillation

00:32:48.700 --> 00:32:49.875
sounds like a low frequency.

00:32:52.000 --> 00:32:57.220
So Doppler shifts are
positive, higher frequencies

00:32:57.220 --> 00:32:59.950
for objects making
sound moving toward you.

00:33:01.160 --> 00:33:05.800
And Doppler shifts are low,
or negative, in frequency.

00:33:05.800 --> 00:33:08.080
They make lower
frequencies if the object

00:33:08.080 --> 00:33:09.565
is moving away from you.

00:33:09.565 --> 00:33:11.500
It's just the physical
characteristics

00:33:11.500 --> 00:33:13.460
of sound coupled with movement.

00:33:16.450 --> 00:33:17.310
OK.

00:33:17.310 --> 00:33:23.090
In the case of these positive
Doppler shifted echoes,

00:33:23.090 --> 00:33:26.280
we know either that
the object that

00:33:26.280 --> 00:33:31.040
has been reflecting the echo
is moving toward the bat

00:33:31.040 --> 00:33:35.210
or, conversely, that
the bat has been flying

00:33:35.210 --> 00:33:38.370
toward the object that
is emitting the echo.

00:33:39.610 --> 00:33:42.107
So a positive
Doppler shift means

00:33:42.107 --> 00:33:43.565
things are getting
closer together.

00:33:44.630 --> 00:33:46.320
And a negative
Doppler shift would

00:33:46.320 --> 00:33:49.530
be things are going
farther apart.

00:33:49.530 --> 00:33:53.080
So not only does the
bat, from its FM sweep,

00:33:53.080 --> 00:33:57.140
get an indication of how far
it is away from the target.

00:33:57.140 --> 00:34:00.490
But by its Doppler
shifted CF part,

00:34:00.490 --> 00:34:05.600
it gets an idea of the
relative motion of the target.

00:34:05.600 --> 00:34:07.390
Why is that important?

00:34:07.390 --> 00:34:09.840
These types of bats,
instead of hunting

00:34:09.840 --> 00:34:12.570
in open air-- like
the FM bats we

00:34:12.570 --> 00:34:15.650
have-- these are tropical bats.

00:34:15.650 --> 00:34:18.429
And they hunt in
dense vegetation,

00:34:18.429 --> 00:34:20.670
like the tropical rain forests.

00:34:20.670 --> 00:34:24.020
And there are millions
of objects around.

00:34:24.020 --> 00:34:24.900
There are leaves.

00:34:24.900 --> 00:34:25.659
There's vines.

00:34:26.860 --> 00:34:29.190
There's lots of clutter here.

00:34:29.190 --> 00:34:32.099
What the bat is interested
in is not stationary clutter.

00:34:33.300 --> 00:34:36.670
Presumably, things that are
Doppler shifted all the same.

00:34:36.670 --> 00:34:39.650
But something that is
moving in all this clutter.

00:34:39.650 --> 00:34:41.370
It's very interested
in moving objects

00:34:41.370 --> 00:34:43.005
because that's a
life form, perhaps.

00:34:44.250 --> 00:34:47.389
And just imagine the
kind of a Doppler shift

00:34:47.389 --> 00:34:50.670
that would be made
by a moth, first

00:34:50.670 --> 00:34:53.909
beating its wing toward
you, if you were the bat.

00:34:53.909 --> 00:34:56.980
And then beating its wing
downward, and away, from you.

00:34:56.980 --> 00:34:57.480
OK.

00:34:57.480 --> 00:35:01.180
That's a very complicated
positive and negative Doppler

00:35:01.180 --> 00:35:05.430
shift that the bat would
pick up on its return echo.

00:35:05.430 --> 00:35:08.540
And that would be a very
interesting target to the bat.

00:35:08.540 --> 00:35:09.050
Yeah.

00:35:09.050 --> 00:35:12.026
AUDIENCE: And how do they
tell that the difference is

00:35:12.026 --> 00:35:14.436
when they're moving versus
if the object is [INAUDIBLE]?

00:35:14.436 --> 00:35:15.560
PROFESSOR: They don't care.

00:35:15.560 --> 00:35:19.410
All they care about is that
they might be getting thousands

00:35:19.410 --> 00:35:24.010
of Doppler shifted echoes from
the targets in front of them.

00:35:24.010 --> 00:35:27.330
Let's say they're flying toward
a whole bunch of tropical rain

00:35:27.330 --> 00:35:28.862
forest vegetation.

00:35:28.862 --> 00:35:31.320
There are going to be thousands
of positive Doppler shifted

00:35:31.320 --> 00:35:32.020
echoes.

00:35:32.020 --> 00:35:37.160
And then something is moving
away from them, or toward them,

00:35:37.160 --> 00:35:39.340
faster than the background.

00:35:39.340 --> 00:35:41.040
All they care is that.

00:35:41.040 --> 00:35:44.110
It's Doppler shifted different
relative to the background.

00:35:45.680 --> 00:35:47.820
They're just looking
for something special.

00:35:47.820 --> 00:35:51.360
That is, something that's moving
relative to the background.

00:35:54.550 --> 00:35:55.830
Any other questions on that?

00:36:00.310 --> 00:36:07.290
So you can, of course,
design sonar systems.

00:36:07.290 --> 00:36:13.100
Submarine sonar systems work by
sending out a pulse of sound,

00:36:13.100 --> 00:36:15.220
and listening for the echo.

00:36:15.220 --> 00:36:17.730
And most of the kinds
of sonar systems

00:36:17.730 --> 00:36:21.480
that we have send out a
ping, which is a frequency

00:36:21.480 --> 00:36:24.800
swept signal, and
listen for the echo.

00:36:24.800 --> 00:36:28.315
Because it's mostly interested
in the distance from a target,

00:36:28.315 --> 00:36:30.620
and whether there's
a target out there.

00:36:30.620 --> 00:36:35.180
This is a very unusual type
of echolocation, or sonar,

00:36:35.180 --> 00:36:35.680
if you will.

00:36:38.540 --> 00:36:39.900
Now why am I bringing this up?

00:36:39.900 --> 00:36:42.160
Well, it's very
interesting because the bat

00:36:42.160 --> 00:36:45.580
gets two queues
instead of just one.

00:36:45.580 --> 00:36:52.230
Also because a lot of work on
bat cortex has used CFFM bats.

00:36:52.230 --> 00:36:55.740
And one of the most popular
has been the so-called mustache

00:36:55.740 --> 00:37:00.950
bat, I believe because
it has a noseleaf that's

00:37:00.950 --> 00:37:03.920
between its upper lip--
it looks like a mustache--

00:37:03.920 --> 00:37:04.887
and its nostrils.

00:37:04.887 --> 00:37:06.220
So it's called the mustache bat.

00:37:07.310 --> 00:37:09.700
And a lot of this
work has been done

00:37:09.700 --> 00:37:14.900
by a researcher, who is
still active, at Washington

00:37:14.900 --> 00:37:16.480
University in Saint Louis.

00:37:16.480 --> 00:37:20.000
And his name is Nobua Suga.

00:37:25.770 --> 00:37:29.280
And he was the first,
really, to work successfully

00:37:29.280 --> 00:37:30.835
on the bat auditory cortex.

00:37:33.100 --> 00:37:39.680
A lot of his work comes from
the 1970s, '80s, and '90s.

00:37:39.680 --> 00:37:43.280
And before I explain this
bottom part of this slide,

00:37:43.280 --> 00:37:47.030
let me just go on and show
you the kinds of experiments

00:37:47.030 --> 00:37:47.835
that Suga did.

00:37:47.835 --> 00:37:52.020
And here's one from one of
his publications in the 1980s.

00:37:52.020 --> 00:37:57.540
So Suga's work was innovative
because he played around--

00:37:57.540 --> 00:38:01.020
well, first he rationalized, OK.

00:38:01.020 --> 00:38:04.430
I could try any sound
system I'd like to.

00:38:04.430 --> 00:38:05.990
I could try clicks.

00:38:05.990 --> 00:38:07.600
I could try pure tones.

00:38:07.600 --> 00:38:09.480
I could try noise.

00:38:09.480 --> 00:38:10.900
I could try speech.

00:38:10.900 --> 00:38:14.650
I could try-- but why don't
I try what the bat listens to

00:38:14.650 --> 00:38:16.220
over and over?

00:38:16.220 --> 00:38:17.815
It listens to a pulse.

00:38:19.170 --> 00:38:21.120
And then a little
bit later, an echo.

00:38:22.460 --> 00:38:26.470
And this turned out to be
a very, very wise choice,

00:38:26.470 --> 00:38:28.040
as we'll see in a minute.

00:38:28.040 --> 00:38:30.710
Secondly, about the
time of the 1970s

00:38:30.710 --> 00:38:34.840
and '80s, speech
researchers in human speech

00:38:34.840 --> 00:38:37.831
were using synthesized speech.

00:38:37.831 --> 00:38:40.080
Of course, we all know what
synthesized speech is now.

00:38:40.080 --> 00:38:42.170
But back then, it
was very novel.

00:38:42.170 --> 00:38:46.850
And Suga says, well, I'm
going to use synthesized bat

00:38:46.850 --> 00:38:48.630
echolocating calls.

00:38:48.630 --> 00:38:51.315
And here is an example
of a synthesized pulse.

00:38:52.920 --> 00:38:55.310
So this is for the mustache bat.

00:38:55.310 --> 00:39:03.010
And this looks like CF1-FM1,
CF2-FM2, and CF3-FM3.

00:39:04.560 --> 00:39:07.130
So he's just using
three harmonics.

00:39:07.130 --> 00:39:08.950
So one thing about
synthesized calls

00:39:08.950 --> 00:39:13.240
is you can do things like
dispense with one harmonic,

00:39:13.240 --> 00:39:18.150
if you want to, easily take
it out, and put it an echo.

00:39:18.150 --> 00:39:19.830
So here's a pulse.

00:39:19.830 --> 00:39:20.870
And here's an echo.

00:39:20.870 --> 00:39:22.480
It's a little bit
Doppler shifted.

00:39:23.510 --> 00:39:27.720
You can look at the no response
to the pulse, and to the echo.

00:39:27.720 --> 00:39:31.440
And this lower
trace is a histogram

00:39:31.440 --> 00:39:34.350
from a single neuron
in the auditory cortex

00:39:34.350 --> 00:39:37.370
of the echolocating bat to
a pulse, and to an echo.

00:39:37.370 --> 00:39:38.510
There's not much response.

00:39:40.380 --> 00:39:43.250
Suga found that when
you play a pulse

00:39:43.250 --> 00:39:47.800
and, a short time later, an
echo, you get a huge response.

00:39:47.800 --> 00:39:49.640
And that's what's
indicated here.

00:39:49.640 --> 00:39:52.330
So this is the
pulse-echo combination.

00:39:53.410 --> 00:39:55.620
And these are
synthesized stimuli.

00:39:57.520 --> 00:40:00.370
And you can read in
the original paper,

00:40:00.370 --> 00:40:02.400
it looks like it's
not given here,

00:40:02.400 --> 00:40:05.765
exactly what the delay is
between the pulse and the echo.

00:40:07.650 --> 00:40:11.590
But Suga tried various
pulse-echo delays.

00:40:11.590 --> 00:40:15.310
And he found that cortical
neurons, in many cases,

00:40:15.310 --> 00:40:19.550
were very sensitive
to the exact delay

00:40:19.550 --> 00:40:21.930
between the pulse and the echo.

00:40:21.930 --> 00:40:24.195
So they were, if you
will, delay tuned.

00:40:26.310 --> 00:40:30.850
And that's indicated
here, in the first bullet.

00:40:33.110 --> 00:40:35.360
"The neuron pictured above
responds little to--" blah,

00:40:35.360 --> 00:40:36.990
blah, blah. "--pulse
of an echo alone.

00:40:38.290 --> 00:40:41.220
But vigorously to a
pulse followed by an echo

00:40:41.220 --> 00:40:41.970
at certain delay.

00:40:41.970 --> 00:40:44.710
In this case, 9.3
milliseconds is

00:40:44.710 --> 00:40:47.060
the best delay for this neuron."

00:40:47.060 --> 00:40:48.650
So this is a delay tuned neuron.

00:40:50.900 --> 00:40:56.660
Once Suga did recordings from
different parts of the bat

00:40:56.660 --> 00:41:00.600
cortex, he found that the
best delay was actually

00:41:00.600 --> 00:41:04.270
mapped along the
surface of the cortex.

00:41:04.270 --> 00:41:09.020
So here is some of his
work from the 1990s,

00:41:09.020 --> 00:41:13.470
showing you maps of best
delays, and other properties,

00:41:13.470 --> 00:41:15.560
in the bat auditory cortex.

00:41:15.560 --> 00:41:19.740
So here is a side view
of the bat cortex.

00:41:19.740 --> 00:41:21.310
This is looking
at the left side.

00:41:21.310 --> 00:41:27.020
This is the front, where
the olfactory areas are.

00:41:27.020 --> 00:41:30.410
Way in the back would
be the occipital cortex.

00:41:30.410 --> 00:41:32.670
And our old friend,
the auditory cortex,

00:41:32.670 --> 00:41:37.750
is in the temporal region,
on the side of the brain,

00:41:37.750 --> 00:41:39.030
just like it was in the cat.

00:41:39.030 --> 00:41:40.930
And like it is in the human.

00:41:40.930 --> 00:41:41.860
And here is A1.

00:41:43.080 --> 00:41:47.220
And this rectangle
here is expanded here.

00:41:47.220 --> 00:41:49.290
And some of Suga's
maps are shown.

00:41:51.360 --> 00:41:54.810
This part right here--
the biggest part--

00:41:54.810 --> 00:42:00.290
is cortical field A1, which,
as we've seen in other animals,

00:42:00.290 --> 00:42:04.150
is the tonotopically
organized field.

00:42:04.150 --> 00:42:06.465
And it's tonotopically
organized in this bat.

00:42:07.640 --> 00:42:13.230
And these numbers and lines
are the ISO frequency laminae.

00:42:13.230 --> 00:42:14.890
So remember, the
experiment here is

00:42:14.890 --> 00:42:20.120
to go in and sample at a
specific place in the cortex,

00:42:20.120 --> 00:42:22.250
and find the
characteristic frequency

00:42:22.250 --> 00:42:23.670
for neurons in that column.

00:42:25.480 --> 00:42:28.220
And then move the
electrode a little bit.

00:42:28.220 --> 00:42:28.910
Do the same.

00:42:28.910 --> 00:42:29.890
Get the tuning curve.

00:42:29.890 --> 00:42:32.090
Get the CF for those neurons.

00:42:32.090 --> 00:42:33.140
And so on and so forth.

00:42:33.140 --> 00:42:35.470
And build up a map here.

00:42:35.470 --> 00:42:39.710
So just like in the
cat, posterior areas

00:42:39.710 --> 00:42:41.610
are tuned to low CF.

00:42:41.610 --> 00:42:44.240
Low CFs in the bat
are 20 kilohertz.

00:42:44.240 --> 00:42:46.305
We're dealing with very,
very high frequencies.

00:42:47.410 --> 00:42:51.460
As you go more rostrally, the
CFs get increasingly high.

00:42:51.460 --> 00:42:55.920
And at the very rostral end of
A1, the CF is 100 kilohertz.

00:42:55.920 --> 00:42:56.770
Extremely high.

00:42:58.200 --> 00:43:01.680
And everything looks
exactly like other mammals,

00:43:01.680 --> 00:43:06.700
except for this huge area
right in the middle of A1.

00:43:08.210 --> 00:43:10.610
And almost all of
the neurons here

00:43:10.610 --> 00:43:14.940
are tuned to between
61 and 66 kilohertz.

00:43:16.300 --> 00:43:18.260
And you should perk up
your ears a little bit

00:43:18.260 --> 00:43:22.740
because that is where
the most intense harmonic

00:43:22.740 --> 00:43:26.410
of echolocating pulse is,
right around 61 kilohertz.

00:43:28.130 --> 00:43:30.940
And a lot of the Doppler
shifted echoes are just

00:43:30.940 --> 00:43:32.560
going to be a little
bit above that.

00:43:32.560 --> 00:43:35.500
If the bat is flying
toward the target,

00:43:35.500 --> 00:43:38.090
this region goes up
then to 66 kilohertz.

00:43:39.380 --> 00:43:46.100
So then there is an expanded
region of the A1 of the bat

00:43:46.100 --> 00:43:50.690
that's tuned to a very important
frequency for the echolocating

00:43:50.690 --> 00:43:51.190
signal.

00:43:52.370 --> 00:43:57.490
And, at first, this was
called an acoustic fovea.

00:44:08.850 --> 00:44:13.360
Because if you go down into
lower nuclei of the bat

00:44:13.360 --> 00:44:17.110
pathway, and if you actually
go into the cochlea,

00:44:17.110 --> 00:44:21.470
you find an expanded region
of the cochlea devoted

00:44:21.470 --> 00:44:23.010
to these same frequencies.

00:44:23.010 --> 00:44:24.960
That is, you go along
the basilar membrane,

00:44:24.960 --> 00:44:28.991
starting at the
most apical regions,

00:44:28.991 --> 00:44:29.990
and you march down them.

00:44:29.990 --> 00:44:32.330
When you get to the
61 kilohertz place,

00:44:32.330 --> 00:44:36.920
there's a lot of cochlea
devoted to processing that area.

00:44:36.920 --> 00:44:39.860
And so the fovea,
the eyes, where

00:44:39.860 --> 00:44:45.200
you have lots of receptor cells
packed in to a certain part.

00:44:45.200 --> 00:44:47.960
And this is where you have a
lot of hair cells packed in,

00:44:47.960 --> 00:44:50.615
or expanded region of
the basilar membrane,

00:44:50.615 --> 00:44:53.880
where lots of hair
cells processing

00:44:53.880 --> 00:44:55.620
this small range of frequencies.

00:44:55.620 --> 00:44:59.880
So this is very much
different from other mammals.

00:44:59.880 --> 00:45:03.470
And the cochlea of this CFFM
bat is also very different.

00:45:05.600 --> 00:45:08.890
Now, we were talking
about delay to neurons.

00:45:08.890 --> 00:45:13.220
And Suga found a very
interesting area near A1

00:45:13.220 --> 00:45:16.800
in which there is a
mapping for best delay.

00:45:16.800 --> 00:45:18.475
And that's indicated here.

00:45:19.550 --> 00:45:26.000
And the best delays are marching
from short to longer best

00:45:26.000 --> 00:45:28.640
delays, as these
arrows go along here.

00:45:29.930 --> 00:45:34.340
Now they're marked
FM1, FM2, FM3.

00:45:34.340 --> 00:45:35.740
So what does all that mean?

00:45:39.060 --> 00:45:44.840
So Suga found that with his
synthesized pulses and echoes,

00:45:44.840 --> 00:45:47.350
he could dissect this
rather complicated

00:45:47.350 --> 00:45:52.980
pulse-echo constellation
into smaller parts.

00:45:52.980 --> 00:45:55.720
And here's an example of
a stimulus where you have,

00:45:55.720 --> 00:46:00.280
it looks like, CF2-FM2, CF3-FM3.

00:46:02.390 --> 00:46:06.810
And you have the
echo for CF1-FM1,

00:46:06.810 --> 00:46:09.180
and the echo for CF3-FM3.

00:46:09.180 --> 00:46:12.850
And that hardly gave any
response to the neurons.

00:46:12.850 --> 00:46:18.810
Here's an example where you
have only CF1-FM1 for the pulse,

00:46:18.810 --> 00:46:22.220
and only CF2-FM2 for the echo.

00:46:22.220 --> 00:46:23.725
And it gave a big response.

00:46:25.810 --> 00:46:27.160
And you could do even more.

00:46:27.160 --> 00:46:33.630
You can strip off
everything except the FM1

00:46:33.630 --> 00:46:35.365
and the echo FM2.

00:46:37.030 --> 00:46:39.840
And you get a big
response from the neuron.

00:46:39.840 --> 00:46:42.090
So this type of
neuron, then, would

00:46:42.090 --> 00:46:48.800
be called an FM1-FM2
best delay neuron.

00:46:48.800 --> 00:46:50.180
FM1 is the pulse.

00:46:50.180 --> 00:46:51.730
FM2 is the echo.

00:46:51.730 --> 00:46:53.680
And with a certain
delay between those two,

00:46:53.680 --> 00:46:57.390
you get as big a response as
with the whole constellation

00:46:57.390 --> 00:46:58.317
of pulse and echo.

00:46:59.630 --> 00:47:04.510
And those neurons were located
in this specific region, called

00:47:04.510 --> 00:47:05.010
FM1-FM2.

00:47:07.410 --> 00:47:11.150
And their delays were
mapped along this axis,

00:47:11.150 --> 00:47:16.606
with delays going from
0.4 to 18 milliseconds.

00:47:18.290 --> 00:47:20.170
And knowing the
velocity of sound,

00:47:20.170 --> 00:47:23.730
you can convert that
to a target range

00:47:23.730 --> 00:47:27.470
of between 7 and
310 centimeters.

00:47:27.470 --> 00:47:30.160
That's how far the
target was from the bat

00:47:30.160 --> 00:47:32.550
at that specific best delay.

00:47:32.550 --> 00:47:36.300
Suga also found some
other best delay regions.

00:47:36.300 --> 00:47:41.420
For example, FM2, FM3,
so on and so forth

00:47:41.420 --> 00:47:43.460
in other adjacent
parts of cortex.

00:47:43.460 --> 00:47:46.130
And this is really
beautiful work,

00:47:46.130 --> 00:47:53.300
showing specializations for
cortical neuron response.

00:47:53.300 --> 00:47:57.090
And for showing mappings
for those specializations

00:47:57.090 --> 00:47:58.880
in the bat cortex.

00:47:58.880 --> 00:48:03.270
We don't really have any data
anywhere near as beautiful

00:48:03.270 --> 00:48:08.820
on non-echolocating mammalian
cortex that show specialization

00:48:08.820 --> 00:48:14.080
for specific features of sound
stimuli as we do like this

00:48:14.080 --> 00:48:15.300
in the bat cortex.

00:48:15.300 --> 00:48:17.040
And this is really
beautiful work.

00:48:17.040 --> 00:48:20.770
This is Nobel Prize
deserving work

00:48:20.770 --> 00:48:25.530
because it really shows us
what this bat cortex is doing.

00:48:25.530 --> 00:48:27.885
It's responding to specific
features of the pulse.

00:48:29.260 --> 00:48:32.340
And the return echo delay
a specific delay later.

00:48:32.340 --> 00:48:33.718
So it's very beautiful work.

00:48:39.460 --> 00:48:42.210
Let me just mention
one other region here.

00:48:42.210 --> 00:48:46.070
Suga showed nearby, a
region where the neurons are

00:48:46.070 --> 00:48:49.450
specialized to
certain combinations

00:48:49.450 --> 00:48:53.340
of the constant
frequency of the echo.

00:48:53.340 --> 00:48:56.590
And then he showed
a Doppler shifted

00:48:56.590 --> 00:49:00.250
constant [INAUDIBLE]
pulse and CF of the echo.

00:49:00.250 --> 00:49:03.569
So this is the CFCF
region right over here.

00:49:13.730 --> 00:49:14.980
Yeah, question.

