00:50:03.180 --> 00:50:04.200
Any other questions?

00:50:09.720 --> 00:50:13.710
So one thing that's gone
on after Sugo's early work

00:50:13.710 --> 00:50:17.480
on these specializations
has asked the question,

00:50:17.480 --> 00:50:21.810
is this really happening
in the auditory cortex?

00:50:21.810 --> 00:50:25.460
Or is the cortex just
merely a reflection

00:50:25.460 --> 00:50:29.770
of some beautiful processing at
a lower level of the pathway?

00:50:29.770 --> 00:50:35.140
And to a certain extent,
best delay sensitivity

00:50:35.140 --> 00:50:36.640
is found at lower levels.

00:50:36.640 --> 00:50:39.800
For example, the
inferior colliculus

00:50:39.800 --> 00:50:42.330
has some best
delay tuned neurons

00:50:42.330 --> 00:50:43.950
in the echolocating bat.

00:50:43.950 --> 00:50:47.760
So it probably has more
in the auditory cortex.

00:50:47.760 --> 00:50:50.970
But they can arise at
the inferior colliculus.

00:50:57.330 --> 00:50:57.880
OK.

00:50:57.880 --> 00:51:03.060
So that's what I wanted to
say about bat echolocation.

00:51:03.060 --> 00:51:06.760
And now I'm going to move on and
spend the last part of today's

00:51:06.760 --> 00:51:09.000
class talking about
speech sounds.

00:51:10.370 --> 00:51:13.940
So we had this particular
slide in an earlier lecture,

00:51:13.940 --> 00:51:16.930
I think the very first
lecture that I gave,

00:51:16.930 --> 00:51:18.760
talking about what
speech sounds are.

00:51:23.110 --> 00:51:28.070
So speech sounds, obviously,
are formed in humans

00:51:28.070 --> 00:51:33.600
by the vocal cords,
or vocal folds,

00:51:33.600 --> 00:51:38.170
closing and opening during
airflow from the lungs

00:51:38.170 --> 00:51:39.590
to the upper vocal tract.

00:51:41.180 --> 00:51:46.180
And this closing and
opening of the glottis

00:51:46.180 --> 00:51:48.610
gives rise to the
so-called glottal pulses.

00:51:49.690 --> 00:51:54.700
When the vocal cords are closed,
there's no airflow coming out.

00:51:54.700 --> 00:51:56.825
But when they open,
there's turbulent airflow

00:51:56.825 --> 00:51:58.125
and it makes a sound.

00:51:59.150 --> 00:52:00.180
So these are pulses.

00:52:00.180 --> 00:52:02.550
And they have a whole bunch
of different frequencies.

00:52:04.040 --> 00:52:06.930
So this is the wave form
as a function of time.

00:52:06.930 --> 00:52:09.450
Sound pressure is
a function of time.

00:52:09.450 --> 00:52:14.094
And this is the spectrum showing
the different frequencies

00:52:14.094 --> 00:52:14.760
that are formed.

00:52:14.760 --> 00:52:17.470
There's a whole bunch
of different frequencies

00:52:17.470 --> 00:52:18.575
in your glottal pulses.

00:52:18.575 --> 00:52:19.560
It's very complicated.

00:52:21.430 --> 00:52:23.320
To form different
speech sounds, you

00:52:23.320 --> 00:52:26.285
do things with your
upper vocal tract.

00:52:27.460 --> 00:52:31.860
In this case of vowels,
you position the muscles

00:52:31.860 --> 00:52:39.270
so that your upper vocal tract
forms filters that enhance

00:52:39.270 --> 00:52:43.300
and decrease some of
these frequencies.

00:52:43.300 --> 00:52:47.230
And after you apply the filter
function of the vocal tract

00:52:47.230 --> 00:52:52.380
to this glottal pulse spectrum,
you get this type of spectrum

00:52:52.380 --> 00:52:53.680
where there are certain peaks.

00:52:55.210 --> 00:52:58.870
And in the production
of a vowel,

00:52:58.870 --> 00:53:01.370
these peaks are at
different frequencies.

00:53:01.370 --> 00:53:06.070
So, for this example,
the vowel "eh" in hit,

00:53:06.070 --> 00:53:11.660
you have a very low peak, and
a couple of high peaks up here.

00:53:11.660 --> 00:53:13.036
These pacer called formants.

00:53:14.280 --> 00:53:16.410
And they're labeled by Fs.

00:53:16.410 --> 00:53:17.830
So we went over this before.

00:53:17.830 --> 00:53:20.670
So there's F1 here,
F2, and F3 here.

00:53:21.680 --> 00:53:25.800
And certain cochlear implant
processors, of course.

00:53:25.800 --> 00:53:27.790
Try to look at the
acoustic spectrum,

00:53:27.790 --> 00:53:30.965
and pick off these formants.

00:53:32.860 --> 00:53:36.310
And they present a lot
of electrical stimuli

00:53:36.310 --> 00:53:39.140
to electrodes that correspond
to them in the cochlea.

00:53:40.950 --> 00:53:43.120
This one we have a
lot of stimulation

00:53:43.120 --> 00:53:44.940
at these low
frequency electrodes,

00:53:44.940 --> 00:53:46.960
which would be apical
in the cochlear implant.

00:53:48.130 --> 00:53:50.580
And then in the
intermediate electrodes,

00:53:50.580 --> 00:53:54.440
they completely shut them
down, even if there's

00:53:54.440 --> 00:53:56.490
a little bit of
background noise.

00:53:56.490 --> 00:53:58.990
And then they would present a
lot of stimuli at the position

00:53:58.990 --> 00:54:00.660
corresponding to F2 and F3.

00:54:02.330 --> 00:54:07.010
And that's an effort to
decrease background noise, which

00:54:07.010 --> 00:54:09.260
is always a big
problem in listening

00:54:09.260 --> 00:54:10.900
to any kind of
acoustic wave form.

00:54:10.900 --> 00:54:12.830
But especially if you
have a cochlear implant.

00:54:14.750 --> 00:54:18.200
So this vowel, "ah,"
in the word "call"

00:54:18.200 --> 00:54:20.740
has two formants very
low in frequency.

00:54:20.740 --> 00:54:22.310
And one in the middle frequency.

00:54:22.310 --> 00:54:24.920
It sounds very
different, of course.

00:54:24.920 --> 00:54:27.100
And your vocal tract
position is very different.

00:54:28.440 --> 00:54:33.190
And this volume, which is
"oo," as in the word cool,

00:54:33.190 --> 00:54:37.030
has three fairly evenly
spaced formants here.

00:54:37.030 --> 00:54:40.440
Your vocal tract is yet
in a different position.

00:54:40.440 --> 00:54:43.020
And you interpret this
as yet a different vowel.

00:54:44.180 --> 00:54:50.590
Now that's a display that's
not very conventional.

00:54:50.590 --> 00:54:54.510
Much more conventional is to
look at a speech spectrogram.

00:54:54.510 --> 00:54:57.100
So this is very similar
to what we've just

00:54:57.100 --> 00:55:00.570
looked at for bat
echolocating pulses.

00:55:00.570 --> 00:55:05.560
This spectrogram is a graph
on the y-axis of frequencies.

00:55:05.560 --> 00:55:09.460
And now these are more
normal sonic, if you will,

00:55:09.460 --> 00:55:10.690
frequencies.

00:55:10.690 --> 00:55:13.820
These are well within the
human range, of course,

00:55:13.820 --> 00:55:17.265
going from 0 to 7
kilohertz on this axis.

00:55:18.740 --> 00:55:20.460
This is a time axis here.

00:55:21.730 --> 00:55:26.640
And again, the higher
in level, the darker the

00:55:26.640 --> 00:55:28.280
display in the spectrogram.

00:55:28.280 --> 00:55:31.050
So there's some really
dark bands here.

00:55:31.050 --> 00:55:34.300
And there's some very light
stuff here, and here, and here.

00:55:36.200 --> 00:55:44.515
And this is the utterance-- "Joe
took father's shoe bench out."

00:55:44.515 --> 00:55:46.420
OK, and that's what
the sound looks

00:55:46.420 --> 00:55:49.920
like when you make
that utterance.

00:55:49.920 --> 00:55:53.230
So the spectrogram plots the
frequencies of speech sounds

00:55:53.230 --> 00:55:53.790
over time.

00:55:55.290 --> 00:55:57.620
What we've talked
about-- up until now--

00:55:57.620 --> 00:56:01.731
are voiced segments,
which are mostly vowels.

00:56:01.731 --> 00:56:03.980
So in this utterance, you
have a bunch of vowels here.

00:56:03.980 --> 00:56:08.110
Here's a nice one, "ah"
in the word father's.

00:56:09.770 --> 00:56:13.750
And you can quite clearly
see there's a nice band here

00:56:13.750 --> 00:56:14.760
that would be F1.

00:56:16.700 --> 00:56:19.550
That would be about
at 500 kilohertz.

00:56:19.550 --> 00:56:23.206
And F2 is about at 1 kilohertz.

00:56:25.620 --> 00:56:28.580
F3 would be about
at 2 kilohertz.

00:56:29.910 --> 00:56:36.500
And there's a fourth
formant about 3 kilohertz.

00:56:36.500 --> 00:56:39.275
And that's the very beautiful
vowel, "ah" as in father.

00:56:41.520 --> 00:56:42.580
Here's another one.

00:56:47.190 --> 00:56:48.100
"Joe."

00:56:48.100 --> 00:56:53.430
So "oh." "Oh" is a vowel
where, in this case,

00:56:53.430 --> 00:56:56.050
there's a beautiful
stable formant here.

00:56:56.050 --> 00:56:59.070
But here is a formant
that's transitioning

00:56:59.070 --> 00:57:02.720
from higher frequency,
maybe about 1.5 kilohertz,

00:57:02.720 --> 00:57:05.520
down to below 1 kilohertz.

00:57:05.520 --> 00:57:06.195
So it's Joe.

00:57:07.800 --> 00:57:10.430
And there's a
higher formant here.

00:57:10.430 --> 00:57:11.280
OK.

00:57:11.280 --> 00:57:15.702
So those are the vowels, or
the so-called voiced segments.

00:57:15.702 --> 00:57:17.160
And voicing just
means that there's

00:57:17.160 --> 00:57:23.860
a constant outflow of sound
coming through the vocal tract.

00:57:23.860 --> 00:57:25.574
And you can make
these sounds forever.

00:57:25.574 --> 00:57:26.490
You can say, ahhhhhhh.

00:57:27.846 --> 00:57:30.770
And you can just keep
going if you want to.

00:57:30.770 --> 00:57:32.990
Of course, you don't
in normal speech.

00:57:32.990 --> 00:57:37.530
Now for consonants,
there are several types.

00:57:40.070 --> 00:57:42.890
And these are generally
called unvoiced segments.

00:57:42.890 --> 00:57:44.960
Mostly consonants are
intervals containing

00:57:44.960 --> 00:57:47.730
bands of frequencies,
swept frequencies,

00:57:47.730 --> 00:57:49.060
and silent intervals.

00:57:50.170 --> 00:57:52.900
So for example, one
of the consonants

00:57:52.900 --> 00:57:55.760
here is F in the word fathers.

00:57:57.060 --> 00:58:00.380
And right before, at the
beginning of the sound F,

00:58:00.380 --> 00:58:03.520
you go, which is
no sound, right?

00:58:03.520 --> 00:58:04.700
You close your lips.

00:58:04.700 --> 00:58:07.270
You keep sound from coming out.

00:58:07.270 --> 00:58:09.816
And you finally
go, father, right?

00:58:09.816 --> 00:58:11.440
And that's what's
happening right here.

00:58:12.710 --> 00:58:14.400
So that's a stop consonant.

00:58:14.400 --> 00:58:18.450
You stop the vocal tract
before you let it go.

00:58:19.530 --> 00:58:25.020
And the vowel T, as in took,
is another stop consonant.

00:58:25.020 --> 00:58:28.390
So you're not doing
anything at the beginning.

00:58:28.390 --> 00:58:30.710
And finally, you go, took.

00:58:30.710 --> 00:58:31.880
Right?

00:58:31.880 --> 00:58:38.630
When you let go, and
emit the sound of took,

00:58:38.630 --> 00:58:41.095
you have a very
complex frequency band.

00:58:42.230 --> 00:58:44.490
That's generally
high frequencies.

00:58:44.490 --> 00:58:47.520
2 kilohertz in this case,
up beyond 7 kilohertz.

00:58:48.780 --> 00:58:50.520
There's that explosion
of sound right

00:58:50.520 --> 00:58:55.500
at the beginning of the
consonant T, as and took.

00:58:55.500 --> 00:58:56.500
OK.

00:58:56.500 --> 00:59:00.870
Now there been a lot of
course studies on speech

00:59:00.870 --> 00:59:03.610
coding in the auditory nerve
and the cochlear nucleus.

00:59:05.750 --> 00:59:08.980
And one of the findings
shouldn't be too surprising

00:59:08.980 --> 00:59:09.480
at all.

00:59:09.480 --> 00:59:14.985
You have auditory nerve fibers
that have tuning curves, right?

00:59:14.985 --> 00:59:17.335
We've been over tuning
curves many times before.

00:59:28.200 --> 00:59:33.430
So tuning curve is a
graph of sound pressure

00:59:33.430 --> 00:59:34.390
level for a response.

00:59:35.535 --> 00:59:37.220
There's a sound frequency here.

00:59:42.070 --> 00:59:47.776
And then a 1 kilohertz CF.

00:59:47.776 --> 00:59:50.570
The CF for this tuning
curve would be 1 kilohertz,

00:59:50.570 --> 00:59:51.160
let's say.

00:59:58.530 --> 01:00:03.700
And a 10 kilohertz CF
might look like that.

01:00:05.456 --> 01:00:06.420
OK.

01:00:06.420 --> 01:00:10.550
So you can explore the responses
of 1 kilohertz auditory nerve

01:00:10.550 --> 01:00:14.270
fibers and 10 kilohertz
auditory nerve fibers

01:00:14.270 --> 01:00:15.725
to this type of stimulus.

01:00:17.810 --> 01:00:21.040
And obviously, the
1 kilohertz fibers

01:00:21.040 --> 01:00:22.255
are going to be very active.

01:00:24.390 --> 01:00:26.090
During portions
of this utterance,

01:00:26.090 --> 01:00:29.420
for example, there's
a lot of 1 kilohertz

01:00:29.420 --> 01:00:32.480
in this "oh" second
formant here.

01:00:32.480 --> 01:00:35.610
So the 1 kilohertz fiber's going
to respond like crazy there.

01:00:36.960 --> 01:00:41.260
In the vowel "ah," there's a
big 1 kilohertz band there.

01:00:41.260 --> 01:00:44.210
The 1 kilohertz fiber is
going to respond a lot there.

01:00:44.210 --> 01:00:48.060
It's not going to
respond here or here.

01:00:48.060 --> 01:00:52.790
But it's going to respond a lot
at the end of the "out" sound.

01:00:52.790 --> 01:00:54.090
OK.

01:00:54.090 --> 01:00:57.980
The 10 kilohertz fiber is
kind of out of luck, right?

01:00:57.980 --> 01:00:58.780
Its way up here.

01:00:58.780 --> 01:00:59.745
It's off the axis.

01:01:01.940 --> 01:01:08.655
But notice the tail of
this 10 kilohertz fiber.

01:01:09.880 --> 01:01:12.020
If I had drawn it a
little bit further

01:01:12.020 --> 01:01:15.700
it would be extending
past 1 kilohertz.

01:01:15.700 --> 01:01:18.720
So it's certainly going to
respond, right, in here,

01:01:18.720 --> 01:01:21.135
as long as the sound
level is high enough.

01:01:22.600 --> 01:01:26.440
If you keep the sound level
of this utterance low,

01:01:26.440 --> 01:01:30.435
down here, then the frequency
is obviously down here.

01:01:32.080 --> 01:01:34.870
That 10 kilohertz fiber
is not going to respond.

01:01:34.870 --> 01:01:38.070
But if you boost the
sound level, such

01:01:38.070 --> 01:01:41.080
that you're in the tail
of the tuning curve,

01:01:41.080 --> 01:01:45.150
this 10 kilohertz CF fiber
is going to start to respond.

01:01:45.150 --> 01:01:51.410
For example, response to these
frequencies here, this 4, 5,

01:01:51.410 --> 01:01:52.460
and 6 kilohertz.

01:01:52.460 --> 01:01:54.730
Maybe the 7
kilohertz can respond

01:01:54.730 --> 01:01:59.520
to things like the consonants,
if the sound level is high

01:01:59.520 --> 01:02:02.785
enough so that it's
within its response areas.

01:02:04.370 --> 01:02:11.970
So there's clear CF processing
of this type of speech signal

01:02:11.970 --> 01:02:14.710
at the auditory nerve and
in the cochlear nucleus.

01:02:14.710 --> 01:02:16.830
There's also phase locking.

01:02:16.830 --> 01:02:20.430
For example, these
lower frequencies

01:02:20.430 --> 01:02:23.590
are within the frequency
range where there's really

01:02:23.590 --> 01:02:26.090
good phase locking for
the auditory nerve.

01:02:27.120 --> 01:02:30.340
Remember, phase locking
falls off above 1 kilohertz.

01:02:30.340 --> 01:02:31.850
And by about 3
kilohertz, there's

01:02:31.850 --> 01:02:34.070
not much phase locking at all.

01:02:34.070 --> 01:02:37.374
But many of these voiced,
or vowel, segments

01:02:37.374 --> 01:02:38.790
are going to have
low frequencies.

01:02:38.790 --> 01:02:41.060
And they're going to
be good phase locking

01:02:41.060 --> 01:02:43.010
in the auditory nerve
or cochlear nucleus.

01:02:44.320 --> 01:02:45.880
So that's just sort of a review.

01:02:45.880 --> 01:02:49.530
Think about the auditory
nerve response to these speech

01:02:49.530 --> 01:02:52.730
signals because clearly,
the auditory nerve

01:02:52.730 --> 01:02:55.700
is going to respond
very nicely, in terms

01:02:55.700 --> 01:02:59.180
of what its CFs tell it to.

01:02:59.180 --> 01:03:01.610
Now, there's been a lot
of interesting work.

01:03:01.610 --> 01:03:05.566
Of course, I don't have time to
get into much speech processing

01:03:05.566 --> 01:03:08.390
and language representation.

01:03:08.390 --> 01:03:10.650
But I just wanted to
show you some things that

01:03:10.650 --> 01:03:13.985
relate quite nicely to what
we've just gone through

01:03:13.985 --> 01:03:14.693
for echolocation.

01:03:16.320 --> 01:03:19.650
Here are some synthesized
speech stimuli.

01:03:21.240 --> 01:03:21.740
OK.

01:03:21.740 --> 01:03:24.010
And you can do this very
nicely on your computer.

01:03:24.010 --> 01:03:27.440
This is a spectrogram of
the synthesized sound.

01:03:27.440 --> 01:03:30.560
Frequency is on the
y-axis and time,

01:03:30.560 --> 01:03:34.880
in this case in milliseconds,
the very quick stimulus

01:03:34.880 --> 01:03:35.810
is on the x-axis.

01:03:36.860 --> 01:03:39.300
And there are several
harmonics, very much

01:03:39.300 --> 01:03:43.200
like we had for the CF
echolocating bat sound.

01:03:43.200 --> 01:03:45.320
And there's some regions
of constant frequency.

01:03:46.850 --> 01:03:48.530
And there are
clearly some regions

01:03:48.530 --> 01:03:53.340
of frequency modulation, very
much like the bat echolocating

01:03:53.340 --> 01:03:54.780
signal that we just went over.

01:03:54.780 --> 01:03:58.960
Except that now the
modulated part of the signal

01:03:58.960 --> 01:04:02.450
is in the front
instead of at the back

01:04:02.450 --> 01:04:03.550
like it was for the bat.

01:04:05.290 --> 01:04:09.230
And so right here,
on the third formant,

01:04:09.230 --> 01:04:12.430
is a very interesting transition
that's not shown in black.

01:04:12.430 --> 01:04:13.305
It's shown in white.

01:04:14.740 --> 01:04:20.910
Because in the work of Liberman
and Mattingly from the 1980s,

01:04:20.910 --> 01:04:25.400
they studied this so-called
formant transition.

01:04:25.400 --> 01:04:29.930
So the format here
is the vowel "ah."

01:04:29.930 --> 01:04:33.530
And you have these three
formants, 1, 2, and 3.

01:04:34.660 --> 01:04:38.030
And the transition
leading up into that

01:04:38.030 --> 01:04:43.110
is either the consonant
D or the consonant G.

01:04:44.950 --> 01:04:46.535
It's when it's coming down.

01:04:49.070 --> 01:04:54.310
It's the combination "da."
but when this third formant

01:04:54.310 --> 01:04:59.890
transition is instead going
up, it's the consonant "gah."

01:04:59.890 --> 01:05:03.300
completely different speech
sound, "da" versus "gah."

01:05:03.300 --> 01:05:04.640
No one would ever mistake them.

01:05:06.020 --> 01:05:06.520
Right.

01:05:06.520 --> 01:05:10.500
And so what Liberman and
Mattingly did was they

01:05:10.500 --> 01:05:15.290
varied this transition
into the third formant.

01:05:15.290 --> 01:05:24.390
Instead of just having one
like that, or one like this,

01:05:24.390 --> 01:05:26.885
they sloped it any
number of degrees.

01:05:29.740 --> 01:05:30.240
All right.

01:05:30.240 --> 01:05:39.170
And when it goes, I think
when it's falling, it's "da."

01:05:39.170 --> 01:05:42.680
And when it's rising, it's
"gah" if I'm not mistaken.

01:05:44.110 --> 01:05:47.480
So what would you expect if
it was right in the middle?

01:05:49.840 --> 01:05:51.400
Well, you could expect anything.

01:05:51.400 --> 01:05:54.660
But actually, the
observation is,

01:05:54.660 --> 01:05:58.710
as you move this
formant transition over,

01:05:58.710 --> 01:06:00.740
subjects do not report
something that's

01:06:00.740 --> 01:06:03.670
in between "gah" and "da."

01:06:03.670 --> 01:06:06.000
Instead, all of a
sudden, they quickly

01:06:06.000 --> 01:06:09.780
shift from "gah" to "da."

01:06:09.780 --> 01:06:10.500
All of a sudden.

01:06:10.500 --> 01:06:13.700
And there's a very sharp
boundary in the shift.

01:06:13.700 --> 01:06:17.353
And the subjects never report
something that's intermediate.

01:06:19.730 --> 01:06:24.130
So this is an example of
putting the speech sound, which

01:06:24.130 --> 01:06:29.900
can be modulating continuously,
into two sharply defined

01:06:29.900 --> 01:06:31.350
perceptual categories.

01:06:31.350 --> 01:06:34.720
Either "gah" or either "da."

01:06:34.720 --> 01:06:36.210
But nothing in between.

01:06:36.210 --> 01:06:38.580
No gradual slope in between.

01:06:38.580 --> 01:06:40.350
It's just one or the other.

01:06:40.350 --> 01:06:45.165
This gave rise to the idea
of categorical perception

01:06:45.165 --> 01:06:46.570
of speech sounds.

01:06:50.250 --> 01:06:53.280
The other thing they could
do is do things like this.

01:06:54.480 --> 01:07:01.430
Present the black stimuli to
one ear and the white stimuli

01:07:01.430 --> 01:07:02.290
to the other ear.

01:07:03.440 --> 01:07:06.760
And you get the perception,
then, of a speech sound.

01:07:06.760 --> 01:07:14.600
If you don't present any
formant transition at all,

01:07:14.600 --> 01:07:16.590
what would you expect to happen?

01:07:16.590 --> 01:07:19.780
Well, what actually happens is
you do hear something ambiguous

01:07:19.780 --> 01:07:22.480
if there's actually no
formant transition at all.

01:07:24.200 --> 01:07:26.780
If there's a formant
transition, in one ear

01:07:26.780 --> 01:07:29.200
and the rest of the
sound to the other ear,

01:07:29.200 --> 01:07:31.120
you hear the complete
speech sound.

01:07:31.120 --> 01:07:35.320
If you just present this formant
transition and nothing else,

01:07:35.320 --> 01:07:37.910
you just hear a little
chirp, a little speech sound.

01:07:37.910 --> 01:07:40.470
But you add that to
the rest, and you

01:07:40.470 --> 01:07:46.120
get an unambiguous or
categorical "da" or "gah."

01:07:46.120 --> 01:07:46.620
OK.

01:07:46.620 --> 01:07:50.160
These are beautiful
series of experiments

01:07:50.160 --> 01:07:56.690
by Alvin Liberman in the 1980s.

01:07:56.690 --> 01:08:01.360
Now, in cortex, the
interesting question,

01:08:01.360 --> 01:08:06.210
then, if you pull an
analogy between bat signals

01:08:06.210 --> 01:08:08.740
and human signals,
we've had spectrograms

01:08:08.740 --> 01:08:10.800
from the two which are
not that much different.

01:08:11.960 --> 01:08:15.240
The question is, do we
have specialized neurons

01:08:15.240 --> 01:08:22.029
in our cortices that are
sensitive to specific features

01:08:22.029 --> 01:08:22.979
of those signals?

01:08:22.979 --> 01:08:27.250
For example, features are things
like whether these two formants

01:08:27.250 --> 01:08:30.100
are close together,
whether there's

01:08:30.100 --> 01:08:33.954
a formant sweep going
down or going up.

01:08:33.954 --> 01:08:36.890
Do we have specific,
if you will,

01:08:36.890 --> 01:08:40.220
feature detectors
in the human cortex?

01:08:40.220 --> 01:08:42.000
We don't know that.

01:08:42.000 --> 01:08:44.090
What we do know
clearly is that there

01:08:44.090 --> 01:08:48.080
are areas that are very
selective for language

01:08:48.080 --> 01:08:51.019
and speech stimuli in
the cortex of humans.

01:08:52.200 --> 01:08:53.700
So in the cortex
of humans, we've

01:08:53.700 --> 01:08:56.420
talked about there
being a primary auditory

01:08:56.420 --> 01:08:59.220
cortex in the
temporal lobe here.

01:08:59.220 --> 01:09:02.020
And we had the little
model that showed you

01:09:02.020 --> 01:09:03.644
that there was a Heschl's gyrus.

01:09:04.689 --> 01:09:07.729
And that is the site of
primary auditory cortex, or A1,

01:09:07.729 --> 01:09:08.229
in humans.

01:09:10.310 --> 01:09:15.370
All around that region,
an area that's sometimes

01:09:15.370 --> 01:09:17.870
called perisylvian cortex.

01:09:19.229 --> 01:09:23.390
And it gets its name from
this big sylvian fissure,

01:09:23.390 --> 01:09:26.620
if you will, that divides
the temporal lobe down here

01:09:26.620 --> 01:09:30.439
from the rest of the brain,
especially the parietal lobe.

01:09:30.439 --> 01:09:32.760
All around this
perisylvian cortex

01:09:32.760 --> 01:09:35.380
is associated with
language processing.

01:09:35.380 --> 01:09:36.480
And how do we know that?

01:09:36.480 --> 01:09:37.855
Well, of course,
imaging studies.

01:09:39.229 --> 01:09:42.720
But in the beginning,
the early pathologists

01:09:42.720 --> 01:09:46.680
like Broca and Wernicke,
who studied patients

01:09:46.680 --> 01:09:51.120
who had lesions in the
cortex, mostly from strokes.

01:09:51.120 --> 01:09:52.569
But sometimes from
other injuries.

01:09:53.856 --> 01:09:58.390
It showed that lesions in
this region of the brain

01:09:58.390 --> 01:10:01.620
left patients with deficits
in language processing,

01:10:01.620 --> 01:10:04.640
especially with a
deficit called aphasia.

01:10:06.280 --> 01:10:06.780
OK?

01:10:06.780 --> 01:10:12.800
Disorders of comprehending
or producing spoken language

01:10:12.800 --> 01:10:13.865
are known as aphasia.

01:10:16.120 --> 01:10:20.670
And these aphasias are
often classified into types.

01:10:21.750 --> 01:10:26.710
If you're a neurology resident,
or you do your medical rotation

01:10:26.710 --> 01:10:29.440
in neurology, you
will see patients

01:10:29.440 --> 01:10:31.520
with so-called Broca's aphasia.

01:10:33.550 --> 01:10:38.200
And this, originally, was
brought to light by Broca.

01:10:38.200 --> 01:10:41.910
We saw such patients
with lesions

01:10:41.910 --> 01:10:43.170
in this part of the brain.

01:10:43.170 --> 01:10:45.525
That's come to be
known as Broca's area.

01:10:46.570 --> 01:10:50.180
That's part of the
frontal cortex, the lower

01:10:50.180 --> 01:10:52.740
frontal cortex,
near motor areas.

01:10:55.070 --> 01:11:00.750
And the clinical manifestation
is a major disturbance

01:11:00.750 --> 01:11:04.890
in speech production, with
sparse or halting speech.

01:11:04.890 --> 01:11:09.270
It's often misarticulated,
missing function words,

01:11:09.270 --> 01:11:10.220
and parts of words.

01:11:10.220 --> 01:11:15.960
So this is clearly a problem
with producing speech.

01:11:15.960 --> 01:11:17.700
Sometimes this is
called motor aphasia.

01:11:22.050 --> 01:11:24.850
Wernicke is another
early physician

01:11:24.850 --> 01:11:27.950
who saw patients with
damaged cortices.

01:11:30.330 --> 01:11:34.200
He saw some of them with
damage to this region,

01:11:34.200 --> 01:11:39.350
in the caudal temporal lobe
and associated parietal lobe.

01:11:39.350 --> 01:11:44.580
It's an area which has become
known as Wernicke's area.

01:11:46.520 --> 01:11:48.946
And here, the
clinical manifestation

01:11:48.946 --> 01:11:49.945
is completely different.

01:11:51.040 --> 01:11:56.060
In this case, the production
of speech is fine.

01:11:56.060 --> 01:11:58.580
But it's a major disturbance
in auditory comprehension.

01:12:00.830 --> 01:12:01.330
OK.

01:12:01.330 --> 01:12:06.130
So you ask the patient something
and they cannot understand you.

01:12:06.130 --> 01:12:08.385
But they have fluent
speech production.

01:12:08.385 --> 01:12:12.110
It's fluent speech
with maybe disturbances

01:12:12.110 --> 01:12:13.990
of the sounds and
structures of the words.

01:12:13.990 --> 01:12:17.474
But the major deficit is in
the auditory comprehension,

01:12:17.474 --> 01:12:18.432
language comprehension.

01:12:21.670 --> 01:12:26.690
So the question,
then, has always been,

01:12:26.690 --> 01:12:30.270
is this Broca's
area the motor area

01:12:30.270 --> 01:12:34.070
for production of
speech and language?

01:12:34.070 --> 01:12:37.600
And is this Wernicke's
area the area

01:12:37.600 --> 01:12:39.830
for comprehension of speech?

01:12:39.830 --> 01:12:42.670
And clearly, this is a
very simplistic idea,

01:12:42.670 --> 01:12:46.780
in what would be called
the localizational idea.

01:12:46.780 --> 01:12:48.375
I'm not sure if
that word is here.

01:12:49.920 --> 01:12:57.560
But if you're a so-called
localization proponent,

01:12:57.560 --> 01:12:59.940
you would say each
little part of the cortex

01:12:59.940 --> 01:13:01.030
has its own function.

01:13:01.030 --> 01:13:03.870
And they do that independently
of all the other areas.

01:13:03.870 --> 01:13:08.600
So the Broca's area is
involved in producing speech.

01:13:08.600 --> 01:13:12.140
And Wernicke's area is
responsible for comprehending

01:13:12.140 --> 01:13:13.120
speech.

01:13:13.120 --> 01:13:16.890
And this is clearly
from imaging studies

01:13:16.890 --> 01:13:21.210
that we know now is a very
simplistic view, and probably

01:13:21.210 --> 01:13:22.320
an incorrect view.

01:13:22.320 --> 01:13:28.030
It's more likely this
whole of perisylvian cortex

01:13:28.030 --> 01:13:29.755
contributes to
language processing.

01:13:30.770 --> 01:13:35.950
And so people who
subscribe to that theory

01:13:35.950 --> 01:13:37.530
would be called holistic.

01:13:37.530 --> 01:13:41.650
They'd have the holistic
view of processing in cortex.

01:13:44.900 --> 01:13:48.190
And we'll go over the imaging
studies in just a minute.

01:13:48.190 --> 01:13:50.760
One thing I want
to make sure to say

01:13:50.760 --> 01:13:59.490
is that language processing is
clearly a cortical phenomenon.

01:13:59.490 --> 01:14:02.200
That is, if you have
injury to the cortex

01:14:02.200 --> 01:14:06.355
in these specific areas,
you're likely to have aphasia.

01:14:07.420 --> 01:14:11.180
If you have injuries to the
brain stem, to the thalamus,

01:14:11.180 --> 01:14:14.310
you are much less likely to
have any kind of aphasia.

01:14:15.510 --> 01:14:18.240
So clearly, the
cortex is the place

01:14:18.240 --> 01:14:19.790
where language is processed.

01:14:21.530 --> 01:14:24.490
Another thing about cortex
and language processing

01:14:24.490 --> 01:14:29.600
is that it's usually lateralized
into one hemisphere or another,

01:14:29.600 --> 01:14:30.100
OK?

01:14:30.100 --> 01:14:34.160
So if you're right handed,
usually your language

01:14:34.160 --> 01:14:36.830
is processed in your
opposite hemifield,

01:14:36.830 --> 01:14:39.750
in the left cortical area.

01:14:39.750 --> 01:14:41.110
And so how is that known?

01:14:41.110 --> 01:14:45.070
Well, if you have a stroke
patient whose right handed,

01:14:45.070 --> 01:14:47.320
they have a lesion
in the left cortex.

01:14:47.320 --> 01:14:48.460
They show up with aphasia.

01:14:49.560 --> 01:14:52.370
If they have a lesion
in the right cortex,

01:14:52.370 --> 01:14:54.940
there's minimal effect on
their language functions.

01:14:55.960 --> 01:14:59.110
Another way is by the
so-called Wada test.

01:14:59.110 --> 01:15:07.376
So people who are getting ready
to have cortical neurosurgery--

01:15:07.376 --> 01:15:09.750
so why would you ever want to
have cortical neurosurgery?

01:15:27.500 --> 01:15:28.000
Anybody?

01:15:29.230 --> 01:15:35.800
So another big disease in the
cortex is epilepsy, right?

01:15:35.800 --> 01:15:38.817
Epilepsy is uncontrolled
activity, usually starting

01:15:38.817 --> 01:15:39.400
in the cortex.

01:15:40.860 --> 01:15:43.280
Of course, the first line
of attack is by medication.

01:15:44.590 --> 01:15:49.140
But some epileptic
patients have epilepsy

01:15:49.140 --> 01:15:50.940
that is not controlled
by medication.

01:15:50.940 --> 01:15:53.985
And they have seizures
every half hour.

01:15:55.120 --> 01:15:57.530
And it's pretty
much intractable.

01:15:57.530 --> 01:16:02.150
So the last line of attack,
then, by the neurosurgeons

01:16:02.150 --> 01:16:06.140
is to try to go into the cortex
and find the part of the cortex

01:16:06.140 --> 01:16:09.710
where the epileptic
focus begins.

01:16:09.710 --> 01:16:10.960
And then they'd lesion that.

01:16:10.960 --> 01:16:12.640
And this is a
successful treatment.

01:16:13.740 --> 01:16:18.740
But if the surgeon goes in and
lesions part of the language

01:16:18.740 --> 01:16:22.930
areas, you have a patient
that wakes up as an aphasic.

01:16:22.930 --> 01:16:24.440
That's not a happy patient.

01:16:24.440 --> 01:16:29.470
So the surgeons do lots of
tests before such surgery.

01:16:29.470 --> 01:16:33.980
And one is to try to figure out
which hemisphere is processing

01:16:33.980 --> 01:16:34.730
the language.

01:16:34.730 --> 01:16:36.490
So they do the Wada test.

01:16:36.490 --> 01:16:38.010
Has anybody heard
of the Wada test?

01:16:39.800 --> 01:16:40.300
OK.

01:16:40.300 --> 01:16:44.320
They take the patient, of
course, and-- if they're smart

01:16:44.320 --> 01:16:46.120
and they plan ahead,
the patient is seated.

01:16:47.670 --> 01:16:48.170
OK?

01:16:48.170 --> 01:16:51.960
And they have a carotid
artery on the left side,

01:16:51.960 --> 01:16:53.800
and a carotid artery
on the right side.

01:16:55.090 --> 01:16:58.150
And into the carotid
artery is injected

01:16:58.150 --> 01:17:00.710
a quick acting
barbiturate anesthetic.

01:17:02.580 --> 01:17:06.570
On one side, that carotid
artery feeds one hemisphere

01:17:06.570 --> 01:17:08.470
of the cortex and not the other.

01:17:09.860 --> 01:17:11.770
So the patient is seated
because the patient

01:17:11.770 --> 01:17:13.270
is likely to slump
because they're

01:17:13.270 --> 01:17:14.700
going to have some
motor problems.

01:17:14.700 --> 01:17:19.100
And the patient might fall
over if they were standing up.

01:17:19.100 --> 01:17:21.270
But in the test, the
patient is supposed

01:17:21.270 --> 01:17:25.580
to recite from reading
or from memory.

01:17:25.580 --> 01:17:27.760
And the anesthetic is injected.

01:17:27.760 --> 01:17:30.870
And as soon as that anesthetic
hits the hemisphere that's

01:17:30.870 --> 01:17:35.050
processing language, the
patient stops reciting.

01:17:35.050 --> 01:17:38.760
That's if they injected
on the correct side.

01:17:38.760 --> 01:17:40.310
If they injected
on the other side,

01:17:40.310 --> 01:17:42.760
the patient keeps
reading, keeps reciting.

01:17:42.760 --> 01:17:43.965
So that's the Wada test.

01:17:48.215 --> 01:18:08.570
Language function is
mostly in one hemisphere

01:18:08.570 --> 01:18:12.700
in right handed individuals
In left handers,

01:18:12.700 --> 01:18:14.460
things are a little
bit different.

01:18:14.460 --> 01:18:16.790
Left handed
individuals sometimes

01:18:16.790 --> 01:18:20.790
have the opposite
hemispheric dominance.

01:18:20.790 --> 01:18:22.930
Sometimes they have
language function

01:18:22.930 --> 01:18:24.110
distributed bilaterally.

01:18:25.770 --> 01:18:28.240
Sometimes they have
language function

01:18:28.240 --> 01:18:31.691
in the same side as
their handedness.

01:18:31.691 --> 01:18:32.190
OK.

01:18:32.190 --> 01:18:36.510
But for this, I'm talking
about right handers, OK?

01:18:36.510 --> 01:18:38.090
Here's some very
interesting work

01:18:38.090 --> 01:18:43.630
looking at the language
areas in people.

01:18:46.000 --> 01:18:49.480
In postmortem, material has
been done by Al Galaburda.

01:18:49.480 --> 01:18:52.425
So he's at Beth Israel
Deaconess Hospital now.

01:18:53.430 --> 01:18:58.157
And he looked at
the left hemisphere

01:18:58.157 --> 01:18:59.240
and the right hemispheres.

01:19:00.370 --> 01:19:04.610
And he looked at the very,
of course, closely associated

01:19:04.610 --> 01:19:07.800
language areas,
especially right near A1.

01:19:09.360 --> 01:19:13.770
And so here is-- you can't see
them on a side view like this--

01:19:13.770 --> 01:19:18.740
but if you cut off the top of
the cortex, which you can do.

01:19:18.740 --> 01:19:20.560
This is postmortem material.

01:19:20.560 --> 01:19:25.350
You look down on the superior
surface of the temporal lobe,

01:19:25.350 --> 01:19:27.540
you see these views here.

01:19:27.540 --> 01:19:33.720
And the area that's just caudal
to the primary auditory cortex

01:19:33.720 --> 01:19:35.150
is called the plenum temporally.

01:19:36.760 --> 01:19:41.350
And there are clearly some
left-right asymmetries

01:19:41.350 --> 01:19:45.920
in that region of the brain
that almost certainly relate

01:19:45.920 --> 01:19:48.040
to language processing
in that area.

01:19:49.481 --> 01:19:49.980
OK?

01:19:49.980 --> 01:19:53.500
So there are
anatomical asymmetries

01:19:53.500 --> 01:19:55.560
in the perisylvian regions.

01:19:55.560 --> 01:19:57.890
And so this is the first
time in our course,

01:19:57.890 --> 01:20:02.010
now, where right and left
makes a big difference.

01:20:02.010 --> 01:20:04.330
All along, we said
it doesn't matter

01:20:04.330 --> 01:20:06.505
if we simulated the right
ear or the left ear.

01:20:06.505 --> 01:20:09.860
And here, clearly, there
is a dominant hemisphere

01:20:09.860 --> 01:20:10.800
for language.

01:20:14.560 --> 01:20:17.710
Now finally,
imaging studies have

01:20:17.710 --> 01:20:21.950
shown us a great deal about
the cortical processing

01:20:21.950 --> 01:20:22.650
of language.

01:20:22.650 --> 01:20:28.060
And here's data from a pet
study, in which the subjects

01:20:28.060 --> 01:20:30.790
are listening to
language stimuli.

01:20:32.300 --> 01:20:36.020
And these happen to be
French speaking subjects.

01:20:36.020 --> 01:20:38.785
So the last condition
is a story in French.

01:20:39.950 --> 01:20:44.930
And obviously, the subjects
understood the story.

01:20:44.930 --> 01:20:47.420
They could tell you
what was going on.

01:20:47.420 --> 01:20:50.700
And these are, by the way,
right handed subjects.

01:20:50.700 --> 01:20:55.570
And here's the imaging of the
areas in the left hemisphere,

01:20:55.570 --> 01:20:58.209
which would be expected to
be the dominant hemisphere

01:20:58.209 --> 01:20:58.750
for language.

01:21:00.000 --> 01:21:01.500
And this is in the
other hemisphere,

01:21:01.500 --> 01:21:03.350
which shows a lot
less activation.

01:21:05.730 --> 01:21:09.260
The activation in the areas
where the subjects were

01:21:09.260 --> 01:21:12.690
listening to language
they understood

01:21:12.690 --> 01:21:18.190
is the superior temporal
area, superior temporal gyrus.

01:21:18.190 --> 01:21:21.372
That's including the temporal
pole here, in purple.

01:21:21.372 --> 01:21:22.830
You can't see the
yellow very well.

01:21:22.830 --> 01:21:27.060
But believe there's a
lot of activation here.

01:21:27.060 --> 01:21:33.080
This blue area, labeled
IFG inferior frontal gyrus,

01:21:33.080 --> 01:21:34.345
this is Broca's area.

01:21:36.520 --> 01:21:38.980
And why does it light up
if Broca's area is only

01:21:38.980 --> 01:21:40.370
a motor area?

01:21:40.370 --> 01:21:43.280
It's clearly involved
in motor functions.

01:21:43.280 --> 01:21:49.730
But here is imaging results from
subjects just listening, not

01:21:49.730 --> 01:21:53.000
producing language, where
Broca's area lights up.

01:21:53.000 --> 01:21:56.050
It's activated on
the dominant side,

01:21:56.050 --> 01:21:57.440
just in the listening task.

01:21:59.260 --> 01:22:03.120
Contrast that to when the
subjects were listening

01:22:03.120 --> 01:22:07.390
to a story in a language
that they did not understand,

01:22:07.390 --> 01:22:09.490
this language is called Tamil.

01:22:09.490 --> 01:22:11.170
And none of the
subjects could speak it.

01:22:11.170 --> 01:22:15.730
There's hardly any
activation in the original.

01:22:15.730 --> 01:22:19.020
There's a little bit
of yellow activation

01:22:19.020 --> 01:22:22.080
near the primary
auditory cortex.

01:22:22.080 --> 01:22:24.490
It's pretty symmetric,
left to right.

01:22:24.490 --> 01:22:26.010
And that's just
what you'd expect

01:22:26.010 --> 01:22:30.230
if you were, for example,
given pure tones or noise.

01:22:30.230 --> 01:22:35.120
This is a nice control because,
presumably, this language

01:22:35.120 --> 01:22:37.033
has about the same
frequency content.

01:22:38.450 --> 01:22:41.580
And other factors are fairly
similar between these two

01:22:41.580 --> 01:22:42.250
languages.

01:22:42.250 --> 01:22:44.510
The one difference
is the subjects

01:22:44.510 --> 01:22:48.310
were not perceptually aware
of what they were learning

01:22:48.310 --> 01:22:51.065
about in the story, in the
case of the unfamiliar.

01:22:52.870 --> 01:22:55.330
These intermediate
conditions, some

01:22:55.330 --> 01:22:59.250
of them having pseudo words
and anomalous sentences,

01:22:59.250 --> 01:23:03.230
didn't light up the language
areas to a great degree.

01:23:03.230 --> 01:23:06.870
But listening to a list, in this
case, of French words-- which

01:23:06.870 --> 01:23:11.490
the subjects were familiar
to-- again, showed activation.

01:23:11.490 --> 01:23:14.690
I'll point out to
you in Broca's area

01:23:14.690 --> 01:23:17.850
in the dominant hemisphere, in
these right handed subjects.

01:23:17.850 --> 01:23:21.780
So again, clearly,
just a listening task

01:23:21.780 --> 01:23:24.180
can light up Broca's area.

01:23:24.180 --> 01:23:27.125
And so that is a
very clear example.

01:23:28.220 --> 01:23:32.170
I'll show you that
these so-called motor

01:23:32.170 --> 01:23:34.480
areas, like Broca's
area, are involved

01:23:34.480 --> 01:23:41.150
in listening and cortex
processing of language stimuli.

01:23:41.150 --> 01:23:46.100
It's not just involved in
motor production of speech,

01:23:46.100 --> 01:23:51.680
even though what we call
clinically Broca's aphasia

01:23:51.680 --> 01:23:53.720
has a major disturbance
in speech production.

01:23:55.850 --> 01:23:56.850
OK.

01:23:56.850 --> 01:23:58.850
And one final thing
to leave you with.

01:24:00.900 --> 01:24:05.170
Broca's area tends to
light up, in this case,

01:24:05.170 --> 01:24:07.950
in fairly simple stimuli.

01:24:07.950 --> 01:24:11.160
But it tends to light
up in other studies,

01:24:11.160 --> 01:24:13.340
like in cases where
the substances have

01:24:13.340 --> 01:24:17.390
difficult grammar
or complex meaning.

01:24:17.390 --> 01:24:19.070
And so the subjects,
you can imagine,

01:24:19.070 --> 01:24:21.980
are really listening
hard and trying

01:24:21.980 --> 01:24:23.860
to figure out the meaning
of a sentence that

01:24:23.860 --> 01:24:25.260
has a complicated grammar.

01:24:25.260 --> 01:24:27.610
I think we've all
written such senses.

01:24:27.610 --> 01:24:30.270
We've all tried to read
them from other writers.

01:24:30.270 --> 01:24:34.310
And it takes a lot of brain
power, then, to decode that,

01:24:34.310 --> 01:24:36.290
and figure out the meaning.

01:24:36.290 --> 01:24:39.460
And maybe that's
what happens here.

01:24:39.460 --> 01:24:41.860
Broca's area's called
in when the task gets

01:24:41.860 --> 01:24:45.390
more difficult than just
a simple list of words.

01:24:45.390 --> 01:24:46.610
In this case, it lit up.

01:24:46.610 --> 01:24:50.020
And in other studies, it's
clearly showing more activation

01:24:50.020 --> 01:24:52.252
when the task gets
more difficult.

01:24:55.521 --> 01:24:56.020
OK.

01:24:56.020 --> 01:24:57.585
So we're out of time.

01:24:58.920 --> 01:25:00.735
I can take a question or two.

01:25:03.490 --> 01:25:06.443
And just a reminder,
class meets at Mass.

01:25:06.443 --> 01:25:09.240
Eye and Ear on Wednesday
for the lab tour.

01:25:09.240 --> 01:25:11.660
So I'll see you over there.

